"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681335","Department of Health","false","2017-02-07","<p>Currently there are over 6,500 people on the United Kingdom national transplant waiting list. Most people are waiting for a kidney. The figure changes constantly as people join and leave the list. Each year around 5,000 people die in circumstances where their organs can be donated. Our aim is to maximise the number of people who can benefit from a transplant.</p><p> </p><p>A seven year UK-wide organ donation and transplantation strategy was jointly published by the four UK health ministers and NHS Blood and Transplant (NHSBT) in July 2013. The strategy aims to increase consent rates, encourage people to be proud to donate and to make the UK system comparable with the best of the world. 2015/16 saw the highest ever deceased donor rate in the UK with 1,364 deceased donors resulting in 3,529 transplants. A further 3,779 patients had their sight restored through a cornea transplant and there were 1,075 living donors, most donating a kidney.</p><p> </p><p>NHSBT run regular awareness raising campaigns and introduced a new Organ Donation Register (ODR) system making it easier for people to record their wishes about donation. NHSBT works collaboratively with a number of partners in the private, public and third sectors to promote organ donation. People can add their name to the ODR via Government owned channels such as applying for a driving licence and paying car tax online.</p><p> </p><p>On 1 December 2015, Wales introduced deemed consent (opt-out) for organ and tissue donation. We will monitor closely how these changes in legislation in Wales affect donation rates.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","62309","2017-02-07T16:00:32.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681335/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681335/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681335/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","Organs: Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to encourage more people to become organ donors.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","62308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681336","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-02-06T09:21:03.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681336/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681336/answer","PQ62291v0.5.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - EU Citizens","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681336/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-30","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the number of EU citizens who have entered the UK since 23 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681337","Home Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme is intended to help vulnerable Syrian nationals. Iraqi refugees are eligible for resettlement under our other, global resettlement schemes such as Gateway and Mandate. They may also qualify for resettlement under the Vulnerable Children’s Resettlement Scheme (VCRS) established earlier this year, which is not restricted to Syrian nationals.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-02T16:40:43.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681337/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681337/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681337/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will increase the number of people from minority communities in Iraq being resettled in the UK by extending the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme to include Iraqis.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","62385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681338","Home Office","false","2017-02-03","<p>We do not routinely comment on individual immigration cases.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-03T10:32:19.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681338/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681338/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681338/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Ravil Mingazov","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 25 January 2017 to Question 60398, for what reasons the Government rejected Ravil Mingazov's request for family reunification in the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","62358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681339","Home Office","false","2017-02-15","<p>The Home Secretary spoke to General Kelly, Secretary for the Department of Homeland Security, on 30 January to discuss a range of issues of mutual importance, including President Trump’s Executive Order on entry to the United States.</p><p>The Home Secretary made clear the difficulties related to the Executive Order and gained Secretary Kelly’s confirmation that individuals travelling on British passports, including those who hold dual nationality, should be exempt from this Order.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-15T13:27:18.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681339/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681339/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681339/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Travel Restrictions: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with the US Administration on its travel ban for refugees and nationals of Iran, Iraq, Libya, Somalia, Sudan, Syria and Yemen; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sarah Olney","Richmond Park","Sarah Olney","62340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681340","House of Commons Commission","false","2017-02-02","<p>The bust of Charles Bradlaugh was commissioned by the Speaker’s Advisory Committee on Works of Art and placed in the Lower Waiting Hall before Christmas. Plans are already in place to install a label close to the portrait bust describing Bradlaugh’s contribution as a parliamentarian.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2017-02-02T11:23:32.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681340/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681340/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681340/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2017-01-30","Palace of Westminster: Art Works","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, if he will take steps to place an inscription on the statue of Charles Bradlaugh, situated in the Lower Waiting Hall of the Palace of Westminster, recognising his campaign to take his seat in Parliament.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","62382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681341","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-06","<p>DFID-funded UN and humanitarian partners are assessing and responding to needs in east Aleppo city and have increased their activities in the west of the city to support those displaced there from the east. This is in addition to ongoing work to support the existing 350,000 displaced persons already in west Aleppo city.</p><p>The UN assesses that the security situation in the city is stable, but we will continue to monitor this closely and scale up our response if necessary. We are working with our partners to ensure that they have effective contingency plans in place for any deterioration. As part of this work, they now have substantial contingency stocks of food available inside Aleppo City, and could quickly mobilise further stocks if required at short notice.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-06T17:20:55.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681341/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681341/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681341/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Syria: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to ensure that aid can continue to be provided to Aleppo should the conflict in that city resume.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","62325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681342","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-02","<p>The UK’s ability to use the EU PEGASE mechanism will not be affected when we leave the EU. Non-EU countries are able to channel funding through this mechanism.</p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-02T17:45:12.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681342/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681342/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681342/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Palestinians: EU Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to her press statement of 16 December 2016 on future UK support to the Occupied Palestinian Territories, that she intends to channel payments to the Palestinian Authority directly through the EU's PEGASE mechanism, if she will set out what her policy is on making such payments after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","62399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681343","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-02","<p>No contracts over the Official Journal of the European Union (OJEU) threshold (currently £106,047) have been suspended by Ministers in the Department for International Development in the last three months.</p><p>A number of procurements and payments were paused following recent concerns about DFID suppliers. We have also recently examined DFID programmes in OPT’s.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-02T17:52:12.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681343/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681343/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681343/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Department for International Development: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which contracts have been suspended by Ministers of her Department in the last three months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","62380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681344","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-02","<p>The UK Government has committed to help 60 million people to gain access to water and sanitation by 2020. The focus will be to deliver results with best value for money in order to control the total amount spent.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-02T17:53:13.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681344/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681344/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681344/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Developing Countries: Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether she plans to increase her Department's spending on water, sanitation and hygiene projects.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","62299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681345","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-06","<p>DFID is in regular communication with UNHCR, other agencies, host states and donor countries. Through this we raise concerns about conditions facing displaced people in winter.</p><p>In October 2016 the UK contributed £9.8million to UNHCR’s Supplementary Appeal for Refugee Emergency Response in Europe. This will reach over 50,000 vulnerable refugees with core relief items and includes rapid winterisation of shelters in response to deteriorating weather conditions.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-06T17:09:25.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681345/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681345/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681345/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with her foreign counterparts on UNHCR's winter programme funding.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","62326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681346","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-06","<p>DFID-funded UN and other humanitarian partners are assessing and responding to needs in east Aleppo city. Approximately 65,000 people stayed in east Aleppo or have returned since its capture by the Assad regime in December. Immediate needs include food, medicine, shelter and cold weather support, such as winter clothing and thermal blankets. West Aleppo city has seen much less conflict, but our humanitarian partners have increased their activities to provide the full range of relief to the 50,000 people displaced there from the east of the city. This is in addition to the existing estimated 350,000 displaced persons already in west Aleppo city.</p><p>Access to the main water supply remains intermittent in Aleppo due to a technical failure in Al Khafse water station, but repairs are being undertaken. In the meantime, DFID-funded partners have been trucking in water and installing water tanks.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-06T17:21:45.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681346/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681346/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681346/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Syria: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the humanitarian situation in Aleppo.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","62327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681347","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-07","<p>We remain vigilant to all incidents involving drones and take the threat they pose to prison security very seriously. A range of methods to counter the threat posed by drones are being trialled and evaluated for their effectiveness across the prison estate. This includes the use of technology to detect and block drones, the enhancement of physical security and working with drone manufacturers.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-02-07T12:59:41.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681347/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681347/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681347/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Prisons: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 6 December 2016, Official Report, column 97, what progress has been made on using patrol dogs to reduce the frequency of drones bringing contraband items on to the prison estate in England and Wales; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","62347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681348","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Government is committed to commencing section 67 of the Serious Crime Act 2015 and will do so as soon as possible.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","62366","2017-02-07T16:04:55.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681348/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681348/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681348/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the reasons are for the time taken to commence section 67 of the Serious Crime Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","62365"
