"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681361","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>Chris Gibb has provided advice to the Secretary of State. This advice is of a technical nature and the Department is currently working through it so we can improve the railway for passengers.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-02-02T15:43:34.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681361/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681361/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681361/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-30","Southern: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 20 January 2017 to Question 60337, if he will make it his policy to publish in full the advice provided to him by Chris Gibb; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","62343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681362","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Department has robust safeguards in place to guard against any conflicts of interest.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-02-02T15:33:32.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681362/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681362/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681362/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-30","Peter Wilkinson","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether Peter Wilkinson notified the Department of any conflicts of interest while assessing the Govia Thameslink Railway bid.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","62339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681363","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Department has robust safeguards in place to guard against any conflicts of interest.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-02-02T15:30:15.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681363/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681363/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681363/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-30","Peter Wilkinson","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether Peter Wilkinson has notified the Department of any conflicts of interest in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","62338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681364","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Government's detailed review into the legality of automated vehicles in the UK was published in February 2015, which established that there are no legal impediments to testing automated vehicles in the UK. This was followed by the publication of a Code of Practice for testing automated vehicles, which was published in July 2015. This established the UK as one of the best places in the world to develop and test automated vehicle technology, and since then a number of significant players have chosen the UK to test their vehicles. The Government established the Centre for Connected and Autonomous Vehicles in July 2015 to lead on this agenda, and has embarked on a rolling programme of regulatory reform which aims to adopt regulations in a timely manner to enable the safe and legal use of automated vehicle technologies on UK roads. The first wave of this programme included reforms to insurance that will require vehicles capable of automated driving to have appropriate insurance.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-02T16:01:06.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681364/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681364/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681364/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-30","Driverless Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the Government's policy is on the use of driverless cars on UK roads.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","62310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681365","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>Smart Motorways are at the core of Highways England’s £15bn investment programme to transform England’s Strategic Road Network, helping to ease congestion and improve traffic flow. Keeping traffic moving reduces stop-start decelerations and accelerations, which in itself has air quality benefits.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England will announce any measures to improve air quality on the M1 between junctions 32-35a when the Smart Motorway scheme opens, which is expected to be in March 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England has undertaken environmental assessments of the scheme during the design and construction. These are available on Highways England’s website.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-02T15:25:17.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681365/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681365/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681365/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-30","M1: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 26 January 2017 to Question 61251, what steps he is taking to ensure that when the smart motorway opens on the M1 between junctions 32 and 35a there will be no increase in NO2 or particulate levels.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","62375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681366","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>This Government has trebled spending on cycling and making cycling safer. Estimated Government investment in walking and cycling until 2019-20 is over £1billion. This includes funding for Cycling Ambition Cities, Highways England, schemes already committed in the Local Growth Fund and a portion of the Integrated Transport Block based on previous trends. It does not include the funding to be allocated through the latest round of the Local Growth Fund.</p><p> </p><p>The department’s budget has also increased to spend record amounts of investment to upgrade road and rail, the biggest investment in a generation, and cycling schemes benefit from this investment.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-02T15:22:09.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681366/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681366/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681366/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-30","Cycling: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of the Department's total budget will be spent on cycling between 2015 and 2020.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","62383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681367","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Department has not provided the information requested in Question 55011 to the Guardian.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-02-02T15:39:36.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681367/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681367/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681367/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-30","Department for Transport: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 1 December 2016 to Question 55011, for what reasons his Department provided the information requested in that Question to the Guardian newspaper in response to a Freedom of Information request but did not provide the information in that Answer.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","62398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681368","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Department has sought, where feasible, to merge sites in close proximity as part of its overall review of estate. Merging the staff and services optimises use of space, ensures value for money and enables effective delivery of services to the public. Some smaller offices have insufficient space to grow as part of the Universal Credit full service roll out.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T13:08:08.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681368/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681368/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681368/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Department for Work and Pensions: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what criteria were used to select sites for closure in his Department's estates review.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","62393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681369","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>Department for Work and Pensions future estate plans are designed to retain the skills and experience of colleagues across the country. As a result, it is proposed that the great majority of employees stay in the same building, with most other employees moving to another site nearby.</p><p>In a small number of cases relocation and redeployment may be more difficult. We will seek to relocate or offer alternative roles to all such employees. But in some cases, this may not be reasonable and redundancies may be required. At this point we are unable to confirm whether redundancies would be voluntary or compulsory.</p><p>The Department for Work and Pensions will be entering into a period of consultation with our colleagues at all affected locations and will be undertaking internal discussions about the options for relocation. It is important to stress that this is a proposal at this stage and we will make a final decision following the consultation process with our colleagues</p><p>It is not until this period of consultation is concluded that we will know exactly how many people may leave the Department as a result of these changes. Our current estimate is that this may be approximately 750 people, less than 1% of the overall workforce.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T13:05:09.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681369/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681369/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681369/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Department for Work and Pensions: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether there will be compulsory redundancies from proposed closures in his Department's estate; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","62394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681370","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>We will be undertaking an equality analysis as part of the detailed planning for service reconfiguration. This will include feedback from public consultation in those locations where this applies. A decision regarding publication of the equality analysis will be made at that time.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T12:58:40.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681370/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681370/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681370/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Department for Work and Pensions: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when an equality impact assessment will be published on the proposal to close offices in his Department's estate.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","62395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681371","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>The list of sites subject to public consultation has been published and documentation is available to view at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=&amp;publication_filter_option=consultations&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-work-pensions&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=&amp;publication_filter_option=consultations&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-work-pensions&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date</a>=</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T12:56:16.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681371/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681371/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681371/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Department for Work and Pensions: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which sites due for closure in his Department's estate will be subject to a public consultation.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","62396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681372","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>The information is not available at the level of detail requested.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T13:11:53.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681372/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681372/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681372/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants have applied for (a) jobseekers allowance or (b) universal credit (i) by post and (ii) during a home visit in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","62388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681373","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>We are not yet in a position to share an estimated figure due to commercial confidentiality pending completion of legal processes and staff consultation. We expect to make savings by merging offices through reduced running costs and making best use of both office space available and taxpayer’s money.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T12:53:37.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681373/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681373/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681373/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Department for Work and Pensions: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the expected costs of the proposed relocation of staff and resources from sites due for closure in his Department's estate.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","62397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681374","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>Edinburgh City claimant count is currently shared with High Riggs Jobcentre and primarily split by age group as opposed to postcode.</p><p> </p><p>The claimant count for High Riggs is 2245. This information is available from the following link: <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk</a>. Figures have been rounded to the nearest 5.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp</a></p><p> </p><p>These are UC and JSA claimants served by Edinburgh City and High Riggs Jobcentres. We are unable to provide exact figures of ESA and IS claimants potentially affected, however the purpose of the equality analysis is to help establish how many people are likely to be affected by the proposal.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T12:45:30.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681374/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681374/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681374/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Edinburgh","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants are currently served by the Edinburgh city centre jobcentre on South St Andrew Street.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","62330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681375","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions is now consulting with colleagues at South St Andrew’s Street Jobcentre. We are seeking to relocate, or offer alternative roles, to all employees affected by the proposed closure.</p><p> </p><p>It is important to stress that this is a proposed closure: we will make a final decision informed by the consultation process with our colleagues. We are not therefore in a position to comment on the potential for redundancy.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T12:38:57.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681375/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681375/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681375/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Edinburgh","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans that compulsory redundancies will result from the closure of the Edinburgh city centre jobcentre on South St Andrew Street.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","62329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681376","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>Once a complaint has been accepted for investigation, the ICE Office will consider whether a solution to the complaint can be brokered with the relevant department or its supplier and the complainant – known as “resolution”. If it is not possible to resolve the complaint, the case papers will be requested and the case will be allocated to an Investigation Case Manager.</p><p> </p><p>Following a review of the evidence, it may be possible for the Investigation Case Manager to “settle” the complaint if the relevant department or its supplier agrees to action that satisfies the complainant. If the complaint cannot be settled, the ICE will issue a report detailing findings and any recommendations for redress.</p><p> </p><p>In the 2016 calendar year the average time taken to process complaints relating to the Child Support Agency, from the point the complaint was accepted for investigation to case closure, was 53 weeks.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Time taken to process Child Support Agency complaints during the 2016 calendar year</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Less than six months</p></td><td><p>49</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>More than six months (but less than nine)</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>More than nine months (but less than 12)</p></td><td><p>76</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>More than 12 months</p></td><td><p>265</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Resources for the Independent Case Examiner’s Office are reviewed annually.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","62317 ; 62433","2017-02-07T16:04:44.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681376/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681376/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681376/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Child Support Agency: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the average time taken by the Independent Case Examiner to process a complaint relating to the Child Support Agency.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","62316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681377","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>Once a complaint has been accepted for investigation, the ICE Office will consider whether a solution to the complaint can be brokered with the relevant department or its supplier and the complainant – known as “resolution”. If it is not possible to resolve the complaint, the case papers will be requested and the case will be allocated to an Investigation Case Manager.</p><p> </p><p>Following a review of the evidence, it may be possible for the Investigation Case Manager to “settle” the complaint if the relevant department or its supplier agrees to action that satisfies the complainant. If the complaint cannot be settled, the ICE will issue a report detailing findings and any recommendations for redress.</p><p> </p><p>In the 2016 calendar year the average time taken to process complaints relating to the Child Support Agency, from the point the complaint was accepted for investigation to case closure, was 53 weeks.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Time taken to process Child Support Agency complaints during the 2016 calendar year</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Less than six months</p></td><td><p>49</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>More than six months (but less than nine)</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>More than nine months (but less than 12)</p></td><td><p>76</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>More than 12 months</p></td><td><p>265</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Resources for the Independent Case Examiner’s Office are reviewed annually.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","62316 ; 62433","2017-02-07T16:04:45.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681377/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681377/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681377/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Child Support Agency: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many peopled waited more than (a) six months, (b) nine months and (c) 12 months for the Independent Care Examiner to process their complaint about the Child Support Agency.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","62317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681378","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>Information is only available for people claiming Jobseeker’s Allowance and Universal Credit (required to seek work); and the number of new claims to Employment and Support Allowance and Income Support who are attending Hull Jobcentres.</p><p> </p><p>The table below provides figures for October 2016 - Employment and Support Allowance and Income Support and December 2016 – Jobseeker’s Allowance.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>The number of people claiming Jobseeker’s Allowance and Universal Credit and attending Hull Jobcentres</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>The number of people making a new claim to Employment and Support Allowance and attending Hull Jobentres</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>The number of people making a new claim to Income Support and attending Hull Jobcentres</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>December 2016</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>October 2016</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>October 2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Hull Britannia House</p></td><td><p>Hull Market Place</p></td><td><p>Hull Britannia House</p></td><td><p>Hull Market Place</p></td><td><p>Hull Britannia House</p></td><td><p>Hull Market Place</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>2,930</p></td><td><p>1,295</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>269</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>290</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>88</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>53</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Female</p></td><td><p>1,480</p></td><td><p>725</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T13:57:50.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681378/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681378/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681378/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Kingston upon Hull","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants there were in each of the Jobcentre Plus branches in Hull City Council broken down by gender for the most recent month for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","62296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681379","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>Over the past few months senior DWP operational managers and commercial colleagues have visited Eastern Avenue jobcentre, Sheffield.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T13:44:26.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681379/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681379/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681379/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether officials of his Department visited Eastern Avenue jobcentre, Sheffield before announcing the decision to close it.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","62335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681380","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>We will be undertaking an equality analysis as part of the detailed planning for service reconfiguration. This will include feedback from public consultation in those locations where this applies.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T10:33:31.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681380/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681380/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681380/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Edinburgh","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when his Department plans to issue an Equality Impact Assessment on the proposal to close the Edinburgh city centre jobcentre on South St Andrew Street.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","62328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681381","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>The reimbursement of travel costs is available to claimants when they are required to attend the Jobcentre for appointments other than mandatory fortnightly signing appointments.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T13:41:38.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681381/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681381/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681381/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what visits to jobcentres it is his policy to reimburse claimants for travel.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","62336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681382","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>We will be undertaking an equality analysis as part of the detailed planning for service reconfiguration. This will include consideration of the potential effect of demographics and the impact on service accessibility. Our merged Jobcentres will continue to offer internet access to support claimants and we are working with local authorities as part of our ongoing partnership to improve digital access and capability.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T13:15:03.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681382/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681382/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681382/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he has conducted an impact assessment of the closure of Eastern Avenue Job Centre, Sheffield; and whether his Department made an assessment of the potential effect of (a) demographics and (b) access to the internet when making the decision to move that Job Centre.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","62345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681383","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>We currently have 1150 UC and JSA claimants using Eastern Avenue Jobcentre. This information is available from the following link: <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk</a>. Figures have been rounded to the nearest 5.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp</a></p><p> </p><p>We are unable to provide exact figures of ESA and IS claimants potentially affected, however the purpose of the equality analysis is to help establish how many people are likely to be affected by the proposal.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T16:25:33.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681383/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681383/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681383/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many benefits claimants are affected by the decision to close the jobcentre at Eastern Avenue, Sheffield.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","62337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681384","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-07","<p>‘Building our Industrial Strategy’ published on 23 January, starts a consultation on how to invest this £4.7 billion worth of funding. It also consults on the technologies which the new Industrial Challenge Fund could support, which include smart and clean energy technologies.</p><p>This builds on earlier consultation by Innovate UK and the Research Councils on potential challenge areas for the Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund, initiated on 16 January. The Green Paper will help to further refine these choices, followed by further consultation by UK Research and Innovation when it come into being, subject to Parliamentary approval.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-02-07T15:28:39.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681384/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681384/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681384/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 15 December 2016 to Question 57076, on the Green Investment Bank, how much of the £4.7 billion investment will be directed to low carbon innovation projects.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","62367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681385","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Science and Society Community Challenge grant scheme offered support for pilot projects in any part of the UK engaging local communities in science. The Department has no current plans to introduce a similar scheme.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-02-03T10:02:30.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681385/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681385/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681385/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","Science","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government has any plans to introduce a scheme similar to the Science and Society Community Challenge grant scheme in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","62311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681386","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-06","<p>My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy and officials have regular meetings with the Department for Exiting the European Union, and both departments remain committed to the highest standards of nuclear safety, safeguards and support for the industry.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-06T14:42:06.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681386/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681386/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681386/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681386/answer/previousversion/33854","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","EURATOM","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with the Department for Exiting the European Union on plans to leave Euratom; and on what dates those discussions took place.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","62303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681387","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-03","<p>Withdrawal from the Euratom Treaty will not diminish the UK’s nuclear ambitions for its new build nuclear programme, and the Government remains committed to delivering a world leading nuclear programme in close collaboration with international counterparts. The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has had detailed discussions with the nuclear industry since the Referendum and will continue to work closely with industry the negotiations progress.</p><p> </p><p>As for research, the UK is a world leader in nuclear R&amp;D and there is no intention to reduce ambition in this area.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-03T13:28:30.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681387/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681387/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681387/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681387/answer/previousversion/33860","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","EURATOM","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of plans to leave Euratom on UK nuclear capacity, research and business plans.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","62349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681388","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-06","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I have given today to Question UIN 62374.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-06T11:26:26.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681388/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681388/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681388/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","Consumer Advice, Protection, Standards and Enforcement for Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what support his Department plans to provide industry in developing detailed plans to implement the recommendations in his Department's publication Each Home Counts, published in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","62368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681389","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-06","<p>Implementation of the recommendations will, as it proposes, be led by industry; and Government is working constructively with the sector to understand how and when they propose to implement the recommendations.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-06T11:25:14.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681389/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681389/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681389/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681389/answer/previousversion/33883","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","Consumer Advice, Protection, Standards and Enforcement for Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will set a deadline for industry to develop detailed plans to implement the recommendations in his Department's publication, Each Home Counts review, published in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","62374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681390","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-06","<p>UK Export Finance has not provided export credit support to Alstom Power for projects in Lithuania, Tunisia, Indonesia, Egypt or India since 2000.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-06T13:27:04.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681390/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681390/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681390/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","Alstom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what export credit support his Department or its predecessors have provided to Alstom Power in Lithuania, Tunisia, Indonesia, Egypt and India since 2000; and whether UK Export Finance have made payments to Alstom Power for losses in relation to projects in those countries.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","62353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681391","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-07","<p>UKEF’s policy is that at the time it makes its support available, it takes recourse rights against exporters, which can be invoked, where bribery or corruption is subsequently admitted by the exporter, or found by a court. After UKEF has provided support for a transaction, if it comes to its attention that bribery or corruption has been admitted or found by a court in relation to that transaction, its policy is to invoke this recourse where it has incurred any loss or expense. Where UKEF has issued an insurance policy, UKEF may cancel the cover where bribery or corruption is admitted or found by a court.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-07T16:56:36.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681391/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681391/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681391/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","UK Export Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether it is the policy of UK Export Finance (UKEF) to take against a company if it discovers that a company it has insured has breached its anti-corruption warranty in cases where there has been no loss to UKEF.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","62354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681392","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-07","<p>UK Export Finance provides insurance to exporting companies through its insurance products. Since 2005, UKEF has not had cause to cancel any of these insurance policies.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-07T16:58:55.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681392/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681392/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681392/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","UK Export Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, on how many occasions since 2005 UK Export Finance has cancelled a policy with an insured company on grounds of admission of or conviction for corrupt activity.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","62355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681393","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-07","<p>UK Export Finance has made no payments to Rolls Royce in respect of export insurance policies issued since 2000. Nor has it made payments to financing parties of Rolls Royce export contracts, in respect of guarantees issued since 2000.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-07T16:57:27.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681393/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681393/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681393/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","Rolls-Royce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, on how many occasions UK Export Finance has provided a payment to Rolls Royce under export finance policies since 2000; and what the amounts were of each such payment made; and in relation to which (a) project and (b) country each such payment was made.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","62356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681394","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-06","<p>Where such information is not commercially sensitive, details about exporters supported by UK Export Finance (UKEF) since 2000/01 are published annually in its Annual Report and Accounts which is presented to Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to these details being included in its Annual Report and Accounts, UKEF provided support for one Rolls-Royce case within the relevant period. The details are: a) buyer credit; b) 2000; c) maximum liability of £40.1m; d) Thailand; and e) aero engines.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-06T13:33:03.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681394/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681394/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681394/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","Rolls-Royce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what cover UK Export Finance has given to Rolls Royce since 2000; and what the (a) type of export credit finance, (b) year, (c) amount, (d) country and (e) project was of each instance of such cover.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","62357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681395","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Government publishes Official Statistics (on a quarterly and annual basis) on export licences granted and refused on Gov.uk.</p><p>They are available to view at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/strategic-export-controls-licensing-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/strategic-export-controls-licensing-data</a></p><p>Currently this includes information up to 30 September 2016. Information covering 1 October to 31 December 2016 will be published on 19 April 2017 and information covering 1 January to 31 March 2017 will be published on 18 July 2017.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-02-02T14:02:55.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681395/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681395/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681395/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","Arms Trade: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many arms export licences have been granted in the last six months; and what the destination country was of each of those applications.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","62376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681396","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-07","<p>The UK has held several discussions with Australia to share best practice on developing possible future trade agreements. This will continue to form part of discussions in the UK-Australia Trade Working Group, alongside scoping of a future UK-Australia free trade agreement and wider trade issues.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-07T17:07:29.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681396/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681396/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681396/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","Trade Agreements: Australia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assistance has been (a) offered and (b) requested from his counterparts in Australia on the negotiation of trade agreements relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","62304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681397","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-07","<p>The United Kingdom is a founding member of the World Trade Organization (WTO). As such, the UK is bound by the rights and obligations that apply to all WTO Members. That will continue unchanged as we leave the EU. There are a number of WTO plurilateral agreements where obligations only apply to a subset of the WTO Membership. We will consider membership of those agreements on a case by case basis. We will do so in line with our overall ambition to replicate as far as possible our current obligations and to minimise disruption to global trade.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","62306","2017-02-07T17:00:11.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681397/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681397/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681397/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","World Trade Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether all WTO rules and practices pertaining to the UK will continue to do so in the event that the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","62305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681398","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-07","<p>The United Kingdom is a founding member of the World Trade Organization (WTO). As such, the UK is bound by the rights and obligations that apply to all WTO Members. That will continue unchanged as we leave the EU. There are a number of WTO plurilateral agreements where obligations only apply to a subset of the WTO Membership. We will consider membership of those agreements on a case by case basis. We will do so in line with our overall ambition to replicate as far as possible our current obligations and to minimise disruption to global trade.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","62305","2017-02-07T17:00:11.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681398/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681398/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681398/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","World Trade Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment the Government has made of which WTO rules and practices pertain to the UK (a) in the UK's own right and (b) through the UK's membership of the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","62306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681399","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-07","<p>UK Export Finance (UKEF) routinely seeks information from exporters about agents and commissions as part of its anti-bribery due diligence and may seek further information from the applicant as part of this process. Separately, UKEF has audit rights that are exercisable in respect of issued guarantees and insurance policies. The audit rights do not exclusively relate to details of agents and their commission.</p><p>Since 2011, 24 audits have been carried out on companies following the receipt of applications for support.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-07T17:08:23.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681399/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681399/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681399/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","UK Export Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many times UK Export Finance has used its special audit rights to seek further information from companies about their agents and commission in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","62323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681400","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-07","<p>Since 2000, UK Export Finance has not provided support to Cyril Sweett or its known subsidiaries.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-07T17:09:09.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681400/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681400/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681400/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","Cyril Sweett","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what export credit support his Department or its predecessor has provided to Cyril Sweett or related companies since 2000.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","62322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681401","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-07","<p>Information on the identities of the companies that requested special handling arrangements from UK Export Finance is commercially sensitive.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-07T17:14:02.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681401/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681401/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681401/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","UK Export Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, which companies that have requested special handling arrangements when providing UK Export Finance with information about their agents and commission payments.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","62320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681402","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-07","<p>The details of agents declared by applicants is not held centrally. A search of every application received since the year 2000 would exceed the disproportionate cost threshold.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-07T17:10:18.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681402/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681402/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681402/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","UK Export Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, in how many instances since 2000 UK Export Finance has provided support to a company which was using Unaoil as an agent.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","62321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682230","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Sewel convention recognises that the Parliament of the United Kingdom will not normally legislate with regard to devolved matters without the consent of the relevant devolved legislature. Both the Scotland Act 2016 and the Wales Act 2017 place the Sewel convention on a statutory footing, as committed to in the cross-party Smith Commission and St David’s Day agreements.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-02-02T16:27:18.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682230/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682230/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682230/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-30","Devolution: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if the Government will take steps to make the consultation process operated through the Sewel Convention a statutory requirement.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","908573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682463","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-02","<p>The content of the Great Repeal Bill will be set out in due course and its content will determine the process to take it forward.<br><br>The Government fully respects the Sewel Convention and is working closely with the devolved administrations – for example through the Joint Ministerial Committee on EU Negotiations.<br><br>This is part of the normal working arrangements between the UK Government and the devolved administrations.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","908566","2017-02-02T16:34:55.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682463/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682463/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682463/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-30","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with the devolved administrations on legislative consent motions for the proposed Great Repeal Bill.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","908575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682464","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-02","<p>The content of the Great Repeal Bill will be set out in due course and its content will determine the process to take it forward.<br><br>The Government fully respects the Sewel Convention and is working closely with the devolved administrations – for example through the Joint Ministerial Committee on EU Negotiations.<br><br>This is part of the normal working arrangements between the UK Government and the devolved administrations.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","908575","2017-02-02T16:34:55.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682464/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682464/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682464/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-30","Brexit: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with the devolved administrations on legislative consent motions for the proposed Great Repeal Bill.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","908566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683075","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-02","<p>We routinely publish Equalities Statements alongside consultation papers and Government responses to consultation on changes to courts and tribunals fees, which set out our assessment of the impact of those changes in relation to characteristics protected under the Equality Act 2010.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-02T16:17:06.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683075/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683075/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683075/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment she has made of the effect of changes in tribunal fees in people with protected characteristics.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","908514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683102","Women and Equalities","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Government wants to ensure that all schools are safe, inclusive environments where pupils can fulfil their potential. The Government is considering how to improve delivery of sex and relationships education, including updating the existing guidance.</p><p>In September, we announced a £2.8 million programme to prevent and address homophobic, biphobic and transphobic bullying in schools in England. Government also launched the Disrespect Nobody campaign to help young people recognise and challenge abuse within teen relationships.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-02T15:15:29.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683102/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683102/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683102/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-01-30","Sex and Relationship Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, if the Government will introduce statutory sex and relationships education to tackle homophobic bullying and sexual harassment in schools.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","908526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683202","Women and Equalities","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Government is determined to see the whole sport sector come together to create a truly inclusive environment for everyone.</p><p>This is why the Government sport strategy 'Sporting Future: a new strategy for an active nation' sets out a number of commitments to ensure all under-represented groups can take part in sport and wider physical activity.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-02T15:15:01.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683202/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683202/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683202/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-01-30","Homophobia: Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps the Government is taking to reduce homophobia in sport.","false","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew","908527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679668","Attorney General","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Office for National Statistics publish annually the highest and median salary for each Civil Service organization as part of the Civil Service Statistics. This information can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb</a></p><p> </p><p>Earning levels for the lowest paid employee are not publically available.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-02-02T15:53:59.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679668/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679668/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-01-27","Attorney General: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what the (a) level of earnings is of the (i) highest and (ii) lowest-paid employee and (b) median earnings are of employees of the Law Officers' Departments and arms-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679669","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Office for National Statistics publish annually the highest and median salary for each Civil Service organization as part of the Civil Service Statistics. This information can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb</a></p><p>The level of earnings for the lowest paid employee of Cabinet Office, its agencies or arms-lengths bodies is not publicly available.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-02T10:37:09.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679669/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679669/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-27","Cabinet Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the (a) level of earnings is of the (i) highest and (ii) lowest-paid employee and (b) median earnings are of employees of his Department, agencies and arms-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679670","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-01","<p>The Office for National Statistics publish annually the highest and median salary for each Civil Service organization as part of the Civil Service Statistics. This information can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb</a></p><p> </p><p>Earning levels for the lowest paid employee are not publically available.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-02-01T15:51:59.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679670/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679670/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-27","Treasury: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the level of earnings is of the (a) highest and (b) lowest-paid employees of his Department, its agencies and arms-length bodies; and what the median level of earnings is for such employees.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","61995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679671","Church Commissioners","false","2017-02-03","<p>The National Church Institutions (NCIs) of the Church of England are made up of five charities which employ staff through a common employment scheme. Information about the pay of members of the NCIs is published in the NCIs annual reports . The Church Commissioners annual report is laid before Parliament and is available in the House of Commons Library.</p><p>The NCIs have two different employment strands: the Church Commissioners Institutional Investment Specialists and the NCI Common Employment Scheme. The 33 staff of the Church Commissioners Insitutional Investment Specialists are paid benchmarked salaries against other institutional investment specialists.</p><p>i) Highest total earnings are £465,584, and include an element of long term incentive payments which pays based on consistent out-performance of the Commissioners’ target investment return over a sustained period of five years.</p><p>ii) Lowest total earnings are £29,359</p><p>iii) Median is £75,050</p><p> </p><p>The NCI Common Employment Scheme covers all other staff directly employed by the NCIs. Outside of the Church Commissioners Investments team, 449 people, have pay managed on a consistent policy, based on job bands. We assess pay levels against other public and third sector employers.</p><p>i) Highest total earnings are £170,239</p><p>ii) Lowest earnings are £17,632</p><p>iii) Median earnings are £38,386.</p><p>Those staff on apprenticeships, internships or training schemes are outside of this pay structure and paid at least national minimum wage.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Meriden","Dame Caroline Spelman",,"2017-02-03T15:49:40.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679671/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679671/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2017-01-27","Church Commissioners: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, what the (a) level of earnings is of the (i) highest and (ii) lowest-paid employee and (b) median earnings are of employees of the Church Commissioners.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679672","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Office for National Statistics publish annually the highest and median salary for each Civil Service organisation as part of the Civil Service Statistics. This information can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb</a></p><p>Earning levels for the lowest paid employee are not publically available.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-06T17:05:39.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679672/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679672/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-27","Department for Communities and Local Government: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the (a) level of earnings is of the (i) highest and (ii) lowest-paid employee and (b) median earnings are of employees of his Department, agencies and arms-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679673","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-01","<p>For 2016-17, Lancashire received £118.8 million in Revenue Support Grant (RSG) as part of the Local Government Finance Settlement. Lancashire had a budgeted Revenue Expenditure of £1.7 billion in 2016-17. RSG was equivalent to 7.1% of this budgeted figure.</p><p>For 2017-18, Lancashire is provisionally set to receive £81.5 million in RSG. Local authority budget figures are not available for 2017-18. Budget Revenue Account figures are scheduled to be published in the summer.</p><p>Revenue Support Grant is un-hypothecated. The funding has no specific conditions attached to it and any spend on services financed by the grant is not ring-fenced.</p><p>Local authorities are best placed to assess, deliver and take decisions on financing the services their communities need, and are locally accountable for those decisions.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-01T16:42:53.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679673/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679673/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-27","Local Government Finance: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of its total annual budget Lancashire County Council received from the Local Government Grant (Local Government Finance Settlement), for each budget heading, in 2016-17; and what such proportion, by budget heading, that council has been allocated to receive in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","62087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679674","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-01","<p>The Department does not make an assessment of the effect of parking charges on low income families.</p><p>Local authorities are responsible for determining local parking needs and setting parking charges which include considering potential impacts on local communities.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-01T17:10:57.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679674/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679674/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-27","Parking: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of parking charges on low income families.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","62132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679675","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-01","<p>According to Ofcom's 2016 Connected Nations Report, there is voice and SMS coverage from at least one Mobile Network Operator to 90% of the UK landmass.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-01T13:35:38.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679675/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679675/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-27","Mobile Phones: Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of UK landmass has mobile voice and SMS coverage.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","62092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679676","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-01","<p>The Department measures broadband rollout by premises and as such does not distinguish between households and businesses; nor does it have a measure of ‘most rural’. Third party websites like Think Broadband do list superfast broadband rollout by constituency - the link for this information is here: http://labs.thinkbroadband.com/local/browse</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-01T13:34:40.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679676/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679676/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-27","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of households in the top 10 most (a) rural and (b) urban parliamentary constituencies have access to high speed broadband.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","62094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679677","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Office for National Statistics publish annually the highest and median salary for each Civil Service organization as part of the Civil Service Statistics. This information can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb</p><p> </p><p>Earning levels for the lowest paid employee are not publically available.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-06T09:41:53.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679677/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679677/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-27","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the (a) level of earnings is of the (i) highest and (ii) lowest-paid employee and (b) median earnings are of employees of her Department, agencies and arms-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679678","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-06","<p>Due to its small size DCMS does not employ a Chief Scientific Adviser, using its Science Advisory Council to ensure officials have access to high level, independent, scientific and technical advice. While there is currently no plan to recruit a CSA this position is regularly reviewed.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-06T09:45:01.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679678/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679678/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-27","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether there is a vacancy for a Chief Scientific Adviser in her Department.","true","Biography information for Stephen Metcalfe","South Basildon and East Thurrock","Stephen Metcalfe","62084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679679","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-01","<p>For details of the latest estimate of the number of homeless veterans I refer the hon. Member to the answer provided by my hon. Friend the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State (Minister for Local Government) (Mr Jones) to Question 50027, to the hon. Member for Liverpool, Wavertree (Luciana Berger) on 10 November 2016:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-10-24/50027" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-10-24/50027</a></p><p> </p><p>In the UK, primary responsibility for the provision of healthcare, including mental healthcare, for veterans rests with the NHS in England and the Devolved Administrations. The Ministry of Defence provides advice, information and signposting to support services for veterans though its Veterans UK web pages and free telephone helpline service and we encourage veterans wishing to seek help with mental health problems to visit: www.gov.uk/mental-health-support-for-the-uk-armed-forces or call the 24-hour veterans' mental health helpline on 0800 138 1619.</p><p> </p><p>The £10 million per annum Covenant Fund makes grants to support the Armed Forces community and has funded projects across all four countries in the UK to support veterans with complex needs. This includes grants made through the Veterans in the Criminal Justice System programme; and the Veterans Gateway programme which will offer signposting to veterans for a range of issues including homelessness and mental health needs through a 24 hour helpline, website and app.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-02-01T16:26:51.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679679/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679679/answer","Hansard Extract  10 November 2016 HOC 50027.docx","Veterans Homelessness","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679679/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-27","Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate his Department has made of the number of (a) homeless veterans and (b) veterans experiencing mental health problems; and whether each of those issues is supported by the Armed Forces Covenant.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","62105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679680","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-01","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answers given in the House of Lords by the Minister of State for Defence in the Lords (Earl Howe) on 6 January 2017 to Questions HL4278 and HL4282.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-02-01T17:40:33.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679680/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679680/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-27","Military Aircraft: Deployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of fast jets are able to be deployed into immediate action.","false","Biography information for Jack Lopresti","Filton and Bradley Stoke","Jack Lopresti","62106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679681","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-01","<p>The Ministry of Defence has not carried out any specific research into a proposal to pay Reservists a half day's pay for training in the evening. The Future Reserves 2020 programme has delivered a significant improvement to the overall Reserves experience which has been demonstrated by improved recruitment numbers.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-02-01T16:29:51.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679681/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679681/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-27","Reserve Forces: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made on the effect on reservist recruitment and retention of paying reservists a quarter day's pay as opposed to a half day's pay for their evening's training.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","62090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679682","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-01","<p>The following table provides the average number of weeks to conclude a Service complaint from the date of submission, in each year since 2014.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Naval Service</p></td><td><p>20.0</p></td><td><p>15.0</p></td><td><p>17.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Army</p></td><td><p>32.4</p></td><td><p>25.1</p></td><td><p>14.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Royal Air Force</p></td><td><p>14.9</p></td><td><p>12.9</p></td><td><p>15.3</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-02-01T16:24:41.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679682/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679682/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-27","Armed Forces: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the average time taken was to conclude an internal formal complaint by each of the armed forces in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","62118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679683","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-01","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 19 December 2016 to Question 56984 to the hon. Member for Rossendale and Darwen (Mr Berry).</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-02-01T16:31:56.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679683/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679683/answer","20161219_WQnA_extract_on_MOD_Pay.docx","56984 - WQnA extract on MOD Pay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679683/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-27","Ministry of Defence: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the level of earnings is of the (a) highest and (b) lowest-paid employees of his Department, its agencies and arms-length bodies; and what the median level of earnings is for such employees.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","61993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679684","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-01","<p>The numbers of Service complaints last year which included an oral hearing are given below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Naval Service</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Army</p></td><td><p>60</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Royal Air Force</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>A complainant may request an oral hearing, but the final decision as to whether one will be held is determined on a case-by-case basis by the body appointed to decide the Service complaint. Full details of the policy position regarding oral hearings in Service complaints are set out in Joint Service Publication 831 ‘Redress of Individual Grievances: Service Complaints’, Part 2, Chapter 5, paragraphs 29 to 34. This publication can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/jsp-831-redress-of-individual-grievances-service-complaints" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/jsp-831-redress-of-individual-grievances-service-complaints</a></p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-02-01T16:28:39.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679684/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679684/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-27","Armed Forces: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many in-service complaints recorded by each of the armed forces included an oral hearing; and if he will detail the procedures for securing an oral hearing in each of the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","62122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679685","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-01","<p>Information on the numbers of Service complaints in calendar years 2014 and 2015 is available in the annual reports of, respectively, the Service Complaints Commissioner and the Service Complaints Ombudsman. These publications can be found at the following address:</p><p>http://www.servicecomplaintsombudsman.org.uk/service-complaints-ombudsman/publications-and-reports/annual-reports/</p><p>Figures for 2016 are currently being compiled for inclusion in the Service Complaints Ombudsman's annual report 2016.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-02-01T16:26:08.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679685/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679685/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-27","Armed Forces: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many internal formal complaints have been recorded by each of the armed forces in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","62119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679686","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-01","<p>The table below shows the level of funding Higher Education Institutions in (a) the UK and (b) the London region, received from EU government bodies for research grants and contracts, the European Regional Development Fund and the European Social Fund between 2010/11 and 2014/15.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Region</p></td><td><p>10/11</p></td><td><p>11/12</p></td><td><p>12/13</p></td><td><p>13/14</p></td><td><p>14/15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London (£thousands)</p></td><td><p>93,408</p></td><td><p>111,783</p></td><td><p>135,385</p></td><td><p>158,230</p></td><td><p>171,519</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UK (£thousands)</p></td><td><p>496,734</p></td><td><p>589,425</p></td><td><p>694,731</p></td><td><p>787,047</p></td><td><p>821,280</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>Source: BEIS analysis of the HESA Finance Record and the HE-BCI Survey </em></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-02-01T16:30:53.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679686/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679686/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-27","Higher Education: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much EU funding was received by higher education institutions in (a) the UK and (b) Greater London in each financial year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","62121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679687","Department for Education","false","2017-02-01","<p>Through the Edubase register, the Department for Education is aware of 19,885 schools with websites.</p><p>All schools, as independent public bodies, are directly responsible under the Data Protection Act 1998 for the collation, retention, storage and security of all information they produce and hold.</p><p> </p><p>The Department provides guidance to schools on how to protect data including the key principles, obligations and duties in relation to the Data Protection Act. Schools are not required to notify the Department if their website or servers are hacked, but in the event of a suspected serious breach or loss of personal or private information, schools should report the incident to the Information Commissioner’s Office.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","62123 ; 62125","2017-02-01T17:08:49.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679687/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679687/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-27","Schools: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether schools are required to inform her Department if their websites and servers are hacked.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","62140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679688","Department for Education","false","2017-02-01","<p>Through the Edubase register, the Department for Education is aware of 19,885 schools with websites.</p><p>All schools, as independent public bodies, are directly responsible under the Data Protection Act 1998 for the collation, retention, storage and security of all information they produce and hold.</p><p> </p><p>The Department provides guidance to schools on how to protect data including the key principles, obligations and duties in relation to the Data Protection Act. Schools are not required to notify the Department if their website or servers are hacked, but in the event of a suspected serious breach or loss of personal or private information, schools should report the incident to the Information Commissioner’s Office.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","62125 ; 62140","2017-02-01T17:08:49.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679688/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679688/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-27","Schools: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will write to (a) Wikihow and (b) YouTube to request that those organisations remove from their sites guides on how to hack into school websites and servers.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","62123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679689","Department for Education","false","2017-02-01","<p>Through the Edubase register, the Department for Education is aware of 19,885 schools with websites.</p><p>All schools, as independent public bodies, are directly responsible under the Data Protection Act 1998 for the collation, retention, storage and security of all information they produce and hold.</p><p> </p><p>The Department provides guidance to schools on how to protect data including the key principles, obligations and duties in relation to the Data Protection Act. Schools are not required to notify the Department if their website or servers are hacked, but in the event of a suspected serious breach or loss of personal or private information, schools should report the incident to the Information Commissioner’s Office.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","62123 ; 62140","2017-02-01T17:08:49.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679689/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679689/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-27","Schools: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many schools in England have their own website; and what guidance or support her Department has given to schools to ensure that websites and school servers are secure.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","62125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679690","Department for Education","false","2017-02-01","<p>As stated in my answer of 25 January, my policy is that no organisation can contract with a local authority to deliver child protection functions if they are operated on a for profit basis. This is the case regardless of organisational form. This is made clear in the Children and Young Persons Act 2008 (Relevant Care Functions) (England) Regulations 2014. The Government has no intention of revisiting the settled position on this matter.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-02-01T16:48:01.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679690/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679690/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-27","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make it her policy to prohibit subsidiaries of profit-making companies from contracting with local authorities to run child protection and other children's social care services.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","62042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679691","Department for Education","false","2017-02-02","<p>We want all pupils to be healthy and active. Since 2013, we have invested over £600 million of ring-fenced funding to improve PE and sport in primary schools through the Primary PE and Sport premium. Evidence indicates that the funding is having a major impact, with 84% of schools reporting an increase in pupil engagement in PE during curricular time and in the levels of participation in extra-curricular activities.</p><p> </p><p>Schools have the freedom to decide how best to use the funding based on the needs of their pupils, and the evidence indicates that the majority of schools are already targeting some of their funding at the least active pupils within their schools.</p><p> </p><p>But we know that there is more to do, which is we have committed to using revenue from the soft drinks industry levy to double the primary PE and sport premium to £320 million a year from September 2017. This will enable schools to make further improvements to the quality and breadth of their PE and sport provision.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-02-02T17:18:41.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679691/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679691/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-27","Exercise: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make it her policy to ring-fence a proportion of the revenue raised from the sugar levy to support the least active children to exercise more.","false","Biography information for Maggie Throup","Erewash","Maggie Throup","62057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679692","Department for Education","false","2017-02-01","<p>Teachers’ pay is based on recommendations from the independent School Teachers’ Review Body (STRB). Before making their recommendations, the STRB considers evidence from all of its statutory consultees, including economic and financial data from the Government.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-01T09:41:35.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679692/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679692/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-27","Teachers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how inflation is taken into account in determining pay for teachers.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","62112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679693","Department for Education","false","2017-02-08","<p>Through our careful management of the economy we have been able to protect the core schools budget in real terms. That means schools are receiving more funding than ever before for children’s education, totalling over £40 billion this year.</p><p>We remain committed to seeing all schools, over time, become academies. The Department continues to support schools to convert and, in particular, support sponsors to turn around failing schools and to enable strong and effective multi-academy trusts to grow and improve.</p><p>New academies and free schools will continue to receive a pre-opening grant to support the costs of opening. Rates vary based on school type, from a £25,000 grant for a converter academy, to £80,000-150,000 for secondary schools becoming sponsored academies, where the grant supports costs of school improvement as well as conversion.</p><p>We also provide post-opening funding for new full sponsored academies to contribute towards leadership and other costs as new academies build up their pupil numbers. This ranges from £10,000 to £80,200, depending on the number of pupils on roll at opening as compared to the academy’s capacity.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-08T13:49:59.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679693/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679693/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-27","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the financial effect on schools of the abandonment of her Department's policy of compulsory academisation.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","62113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679694","Department for Education","false","2017-02-06","<p>The level of earnings of the (a) (i) highest paid employee, (ii) lowest paid and (b) median earnings of employees in the Department for Education is included in the table below and is based on data as at 31 March 2016.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Highest Paid*</p></td><td><p>Lowest Paid</p></td><td><p>Median Pay*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Department for Education</p></td><td><p>£162,500</p></td><td><p>£18,454</p></td><td><p>£34,650</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Education Funding Agency</p></td><td><p>£142,500</p></td><td><p>£18,285</p></td><td><p>£40,300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Skills Funding Agency</p></td><td><p>£112,500</p></td><td><p>£14,200</p></td><td><p>£36,810</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Standards and Testing Agency</p></td><td><p>£87,500</p></td><td><p>£22,438</p></td><td><p>£34,300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>The National College for Teaching and Leadership</p></td><td><p>£127,500</p></td><td><p>£18,104</p></td><td><p>£30,550</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The columns marked with a star (*) are published annually in the autumn and can be found through the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb</a>.</p><p>We do not hold equivalent data for the Department’s arms-length bodies and staff from the former Department for Business, Innovation and Skills.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-06T15:10:41.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679694/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679694/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-27","Department for Education: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the (a) level of earnings is of the (i) highest and (ii) lowest-paid employee and (b) median earnings are of employees of her Department, agencies and arms-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679695","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Office for National Statistics publish annually the highest and median salary for each Civil Service organisation as part of the Civil Service Statistics. This information can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb</a></p><p> </p><p>Earning levels for the lowest paid employees are not publically available.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-07T10:23:33.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679695/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679695/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-27","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the (a) level of earnings is of the (i) highest and (ii) lowest-paid employee and (b) median earnings are of employees of her Department, agencies and arms-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679696","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Department for Transport has not carried out an assessment of the effect on air quality of increasing the capacity of the M4 between junctions 2 and 4 by creating a tunnel for additional traffic.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-02T15:57:13.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679696/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679696/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-27","M4: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect on air quality of increasing the capacity of the M4 between junctions 3 and 4 by creating a tunnel for additional traffic.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","62080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679697","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-01","<p>At a recent meeting of the EU Standing Committee for Veterinary Medicinal Products on 20 January, the UK presented the view that withdrawal of these products may have a significant negative impact on pig production.</p><p> </p><p>The scientific basis for recommendation of withdrawal of the products is to be re-examined by the European Medicines Agency’s Committee for Medicinal Products for Veterinary Use. This process is expected to take two months.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to engage with UK stakeholders and the Commission to ensure that the wider context of the impact of a withdrawal is fully considered, and to achieve the best outcome for all stakeholders, balancing availability of medicines with the need to manage all associated risks.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-01T11:43:22.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679697/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679697/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-27","Animal Feed: Pigs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what representations she plans to make to her EU counterparts on securing the right to retain the use of zinc oxide in piglet feed; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","61983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679698","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-01","<p>I have not recently met The Rt Hon. Lord Patten of Barnes to discuss Hong Kong.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-01T14:19:50.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679698/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679698/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-27","Hong Kong: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with Lord Patten of Barnes on (a) the rule of law and (b) democracy in Hong Kong.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","61984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679699","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-01","<p>While I did not meet the Chief Executive CY Leung during my visit to Hong Kong on 1 – 3 December 2016, I discussed the political situation in Hong Kong with the Chief Secretary, Carrie Lam; legislators from a variety of mainstream parties; and a range of senior civil society and business representatives. In my discussions, I made clear that the Sino-British Joint Declaration and the Basic Law underpin the implementation of 'One Country, Two Systems' and remain the foundations for the high degree of autonomy of Hong Kong and the rights and freedoms of its people. The rule of law and independent judiciary are essential to the success of 'One Country, Two Systems'. I encouraged all parties to play their part in rebuilding constructive dialogue to pave the way for the resumption of the political reform process at the earliest opportunity.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-01T14:31:07.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679699/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679699/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-27","Hong Kong: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Government on (a) the rule of law and (b) democracy in Hong Kong.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","61985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679700","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-01","<p>While I did not meet the Chief Executive CY Leung during my visit to Hong Kong on 1 – 3 December 2016, I discussed the political situation in Hong Kong with the Chief Secretary, Carrie Lam; legislators from a variety of mainstream parties; and a range of senior civil society and business representatives. In my discussions, I made clear that the Sino-British Joint Declaration and the Basic Law underpin the implementation of 'One Country, Two Systems' and remain the foundations for the high degree of autonomy of Hong Kong and the rights and freedoms of its people. The rule of law and independent judiciary are essential to the success of 'One Country, Two Systems'. I encouraged all parties to play their part in rebuilding constructive dialogue to pave the way for the resumption of the political reform process at the earliest opportunity.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-01T14:47:36.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679700/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679700/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-27","Hong Kong: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with members of the Legislative Council of Hong Kong on (a) the rule of law and (b) democracy in Hong Kong.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","61986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679701","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-01","<p>The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson) and I discussed the importance of maintaining confidence in 'One Country, Two Systems' with Chinese State Councillor Yang Jiechi at the UK – China Strategic Dialogue on 20 December, in which I participated.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-01T14:39:37.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679701/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679701/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-27","Hong Kong: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Chinese counterpart on (a) the rule of law and (b) democracy in Hong Kong.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","61987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679702","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-01","<p>Following my visit to Hong Kong in December 2016, I have no immediate plans for a further visit. The British Consulate General in Hong Kong continues to support and represent UK interests there.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-01T14:54:21.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679702/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679702/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679702/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-27","Hong Kong: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when the Minister for Asia and the Pacific next plans to visit Hong Kong.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","61988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679703","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>UK Missions overseas aim to support families of UK citizens murdered abroad in a variety of ways. This includes providing important information about the local police and legal system, and what to expect at court hearings. Officials can also attend the first and last day of a trial and be present at the verdict; and can make or suggest appropriate representations to the local authorities if there are concerns that the investigation or judicial process is not being carried out in line with local laws or procedures.</p><p>We will consider intervening to make representations to the local authorities if there are concerns that an investigation is not being carried out in line with local procedures; if there are justified complaints about discrimination against the person involved; or where we judge that a local delay or decision creates significant distress for those involved. However we do not interfere in investigations or judicial processes of a country, just as we expect them not to interfere with investigations or judicial processes in the UK. It is therefore important that families consider appointing a local lawyer who can offer legal advice on local police and judicial processes, represent their interests in court and raise any concerns they may have.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-02-06T16:57:35.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679703/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679703/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679703/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-27","British Nationals Abroad: Homicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how UK overseas posts ensure that the families of UK citizens murdered abroad are adequately represented in related prosecution processes.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","62011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679704","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The High Commission has not been represented at any hearings related to the murder of Adrian St John. Consular staff do not normally attend court hearings, although they can attend the first and last day of a trial and be present at the verdict. A representative of the British High Commission in Trinidad and Tobago will observe the next hearing on 6 February 2017. This is on an exceptional basis.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-02-06T17:31:51.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679704/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679704/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679704/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-27","Adrian St John","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, for what reason Trinidad and Tobago High Commission has not been represented in the hearings related to the murder of Adrian St John.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","62041"
