t","Keith Vaz","61946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679154","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-31","<p>The cost of the Royal Courts of Justice and UK Supreme Court for the last 5 years are detailed in the table below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Royal Courts of Justice</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£24,336,600</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£34,548,300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£15,900,200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£55,811,700</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£43,288,500</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Costs of the Royal Courts of Justice in years prior to 2014-15 do not include costs of higher judiciary paid out of the consolidated fund, which have been included for 2014-15 and 2015-16 and are, therefore, not on a like-for-like basis.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>UK Supreme Court</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£12,039,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£12,355,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£11,956,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£11,424,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£11,604,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-31T16:08:58.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679154/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679154/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679154/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-26","Courts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the cost to the public purse has been of the (a) Royal Courts of Justice and (b) Supreme Court in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","61962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679155","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-01","<p>Information about the volume and outcomes of appeals to the First-tier Tribunal (Social Security and Child Support) is published on gov.uk.</p><p> </p><p>The table below provides a further breakdown of this information, covering the latest period for which figures are available (July to September 2016).</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p><strong> </strong> <strong>Proportion of appeals decided in favour of the appellant between</strong> <strong>July and September 2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>PIP<sup>1</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>ESA<sup>2</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>IS</strong><sup>3</sup></p></td><td><p><strong>JSA</strong><sup>4</sup></p></td><td><p><strong>Tax Credits</strong><sup>5</sup></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Glasgow</strong><sup>6</sup> <strong> </strong></p></td><td><p>58%</p></td><td><p>61%</p></td><td><p>43%</p></td><td><p>42%</p></td><td><p>29%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong> </strong> <strong>Hamilton</strong><sup>7</sup></p></td><td><p>40%</p></td><td><p>54%</p></td><td><p>50%</p></td><td><p>33%</p></td><td><p>55%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Based on cases cleared<sup>8</sup> at Tribunal</p><p> </p><p>SSCS data are normally registered to the venue nearest to the appellant’s home address. We cannot retrieve data based on the appellant’s actual address, but can produce reports detailing the numbers of cases that were dealt with at one of our Regional centres</p><p> </p><p>1 Personal Independence Payment (New Claim Appeals) which replaced Disability Living Allowance was introduced on 8 April 2013, also includes Personal Independence Clams (Reassessments)</p><p>2 Includes Employment and Support Allowance and Employment and Support Allowance (Reassessments)</p><p>3 Income Support</p><p>4 Jobseeker's Allowance</p><p>5 Includes Child Tax Credit and Working Tax Credit.</p><p>6 Glasgow Wellington House venue includes all appeals heard in this venue, appellants living in the Rutherglen area are normally assigned to this venue for a tribunal hearing.</p><p>7 Hamilton venue includes all appeals heard in this venue, appellants living in the Hamilton West area are normally assigned to this venue for a tribunal hearing.</p><p>8 Represents those cases cleared at a tribunal hearing, excludes those cases disposed of without the need of a hearing (i.e. decisions retrospectively supersede, withdrawn prior to hearing, struck out)</p><p> </p><p>Although care is taken when processing and analysing the data, the details are subject to inaccuracies inherent in any large-scale case management system and are the best data that is available.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-01T17:02:58.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679155/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679155/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679155/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-26","Social Security Benefits: Rutherglen and Hamilton West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of appeals to the tribunal service from appellants in Rutherglen and Hamilton West constituency for claims relating to (a) personal independence payment, (b) employment and support allowance, (c) income support, (d) jobseeker's allowance and (e) tax credits were successful in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","61935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679156","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Class 390 “Pendolino” trains are owned by Angel Trains Limited and currently leased to West Coast Trains Limited, the operator of the West Coast franchise. It is a matter for the owner to determine the serviceable life of the train and to market them as necessary to meet the fleet strategy of future operators.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-02-03T12:58:38.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679156/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679156/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679156/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-26","West Coast Railway Line: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 24 January 2017 to Question 60205, when he expects Pendolino trains to (a) reach the end of their serviceable life and (b) be withdrawn from service on the West Coast Mainline.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","61930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679157","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-03","<p>Since 2011/12, bus miles on local bus services in England outside London have fallen by 6 per cent. This decrease has been driven by a 34 per cent fall in local authority supported mileage since 2011/12. In contrast, commercial mileage on local bus services in England outside London is 2 per cent higher than in 2011/12.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2011/12, bus miles on local bus services in London have remained relatively unchanged with a 0.5 per cent increase.</p><p> </p><p>These statistics do not reflect changes in the use of those community transport services which, because of their nature, are not registered as local bus services. Some local authorities have chosen to support these services as an alternative to more traditional bus routes. The Government is supporting community transport by providing over 300 local charities and community groups with new minibuses through the £25m Community Minibus Fund. The Government also pays out over £3.5 million a year through the Bus Service Operators Grant system to help support individual community transport operators.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-03T10:26:51.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679157/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679157/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679157/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-26","Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the reasons for trends in lost scheduled bus mileage since 2011.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","61940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679158","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>We have committed to a public consultation for offices over three miles and 20 minutes away by public transport. There are 25 consultations covering 27 sites planned. Consultation started on 30 January 2017 and ends at 5pm on 28 February 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The full list of sites we have announced has been published and is available from: <a href="http://qna.files.parliament.uk/ws-attachments/678953/original/DWP%20Estates%20Proposals.pdf" target="_blank">http://qna.files.parliament.uk/ws-attachments/678953/original/DWP%20Estates%20Proposals.pdf</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T16:16:19.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679158/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679158/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679158/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Jobcentres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Written Statement of 26 January 2017, HCWS439, on welfare delivery, which of the jobcentres due to be closed or co-located elsewhere will be subject to public consultation.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","61910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679159","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-31","<p>Under the PRIME Contract DWP has ability to sublet space that it no longer requires, however DWP always looks first at handing back any surplus space to our accommodation partner Telereal Trillium (TT) utilising the provisions of the Contract to vacate space and reduce running costs. If this is not possible a sublet can be agreed and TT act as our agents in agreeing and managing the sub-let on DWP’s behalf, for which they receive a management fee.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-31T12:32:59.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679159/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679159/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Department for Work and Pensions: Sub-letting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what provision there is for his Department to sublet property covered by its Prime contract.","false","Biography information for Anne McLaughlin","Glasgow North East","Anne McLaughlin","61939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679160","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-03","<p>The statistics on the outcomes of Disability Living Allowance claimants who have been invited to and claimed Personal Independence Payment (PIP), including those who have seen a reduced award value, are in the table below:</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 – Award outcomes following reassessment for PIP in Rutherglen and Hamilton West</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Award amount increased</p></td><td><p>Award amount the same</p></td><td><p>Award amount decreased</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan-Dec 2014</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan-Dec 2015</p></td><td><p>200</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan-Oct 2016</p></td><td><p>300</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>200</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><ul><li>‘-’ indicates fewer than 50 cases in the category.</li><li>Data has been rounded to the nearest 100.</li><li>Data taken from the PIP computer system’s management information.</li></ul>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-02-03T11:25:31.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679160/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679160/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Social Security Benefits: Rutherglen and Hamilton West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in Rutherglen and Hamilton West constituency have had their benefit payments reduced after transferring from disability living allowance to personal independence payment in each year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","61936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679161","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-03","<p>This information is not available</p><p> </p><p>Information on Jobseeker’s Allowance sanction decisions by referral reason and constituency is available here: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-03T11:29:45.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679161/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679161/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Jobseeker's Allowance: Rutherglen and Hamilton West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have been sanctioned for not attending a jobseeker's allowance appointment within five minutes of the appointed time in Rutherglen and Hamilton West constituency in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","61937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679162","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>It is important to remember that the announcements made in relation to the Written Statement of 26 January 2017 are just proposals at this stage and not final decisions.</p><p> </p><p>Until discussions with staff have been undertaken, we cannot provide details of how many new and existing people would make up that number.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T16:21:57.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679162/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679162/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Written Statement of 26 January 2017, HCWS439, on welfare delivery, how many (a) existing and (b) new employees of his Department will be based at the newly acquired back-of-house site in Glasgow.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","61907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679163","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>We have committed to a public consultation for offices over three miles and 20 minutes away by public transport. Consultation started on 30 January 2017 and ends at 5pm on 28 February 2017. We will also be undertaking internal consultations with staff in those sites affected.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T16:10:14.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679163/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679163/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Department for Work and Pensions: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Written Statement of 26 January 2017, HCWS439, on welfare delivery, whether each of his Department's sites due to be closed or co-located elsewhere have been consulted on those proposals.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","61908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679164","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>It is important to remember that the announcements made in relation to the Written Statement of 26 January 2017 are just proposals at this stage and not final decisions. As such, no specific dates in relation to the proposals have yet been agreed.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T16:31:31.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679164/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679164/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Written Statement of 26 January 2017, HCWS439, on welfare delivery, on what date further details will be released on the acquisition of a new back-of-house site in Glasgow.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","61909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679165","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-31","<p>There are 846 properties covered by the PRIME contract.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-31T12:11:06.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679165/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679165/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Department for Work and Pensions: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many properties are covered by his Department's Prime contract.","false","Biography information for Anne McLaughlin","Glasgow North East","Anne McLaughlin","61938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679166","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-31","<p>(a) DWP occupies Portcullis House, Glasgow under the Civil Estates Occupancy Agreement (CEOA) as it shares occupation with Her Majesty Customs and Revenue (HMRC), this CEOA expires on 31 March 2018.</p><p> </p><p>(b) The lease for Corunna House, Glasgow is in the name of Telereal Trillium (TT) and expires on 31<sup>st</sup> March 2020, however DWP occupy this site under a PRIME lease from TT and as such DWP would need to agree with TT terms for all sites required beyond March 2018, by the PRIME expiry date 31<sup>st</sup> March 2018.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-31T12:06:17.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679166/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679166/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Department for Work and Pensions: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, on what dates leases for (a) Portcullis House, Glasgow and (b) Corunna House, Glasgow are due for renewal.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","61975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679167","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-03","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-02-03T11:32:28.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679167/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679167/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in (a) Rutherglen and Hamilton West constituency, (b) Scotland and (c) the UK received support through the Access to Work scheme in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","61952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679168","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-31","<p>It should not be necessary for a claimant to visit a Jobcentre to obtain any claim form for Income Support or Employment and Support Allowance.</p><p> </p><p>The preferred method for making a claim for either benefit is by telephone, where the claimant can also request an alternative format. However, there may be individual instances where printing claim forms in the Jobcentre will be helpful and appropriate. Information is not recorded on the number of occasions this has happened.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-31T14:57:00.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679168/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679168/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679168/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many blank (a) employment support allowance claim forms and (b) income support claim forms have been issued in the last year from Jobcentres in (i) Scotland, (ii) England and (iii) Wales.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","61927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679169","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-31","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions staff headcount in each year since March 2012 in (a) Portcullis House, Glasgow and (b) Corunna House, Glasgow, was</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>FINANCIAL YEAR ENDING</p></td><td><p>CORUNNA HOUSE</p></td><td><p>PORTCULLIS HOUSE</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31-Mar-2012</p></td><td><p>72</p></td><td><p>215</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31-Mar-2013</p></td><td><p>191</p></td><td><p>205</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31-Mar-2014</p></td><td><p>187</p></td><td><p>215</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31-Mar-2015</p></td><td><p>171</p></td><td><p>213</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31-Mar-2016</p></td><td><p>163</p></td><td><p>187</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>We do not hold the equivalent data for 2010 or 2011.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-31T12:01:38.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679169/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679169/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Department for Work and Pensions: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his Department's staff headcount was in each year since 2010 at (a) Portcullis House, Glasgow and (b) Corunna House, Glasgow.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","61968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679170","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>The vast majority of our benefit claims are now made on line or by telephone. The total ESA claims we receive on a clerical ESA 1 is usually around 5% and for JSA claims clerical cases are issued in less than 1% of cases as a general rule. In all cases when a clerical form is required it is dispatched on the same day if the request is received before 12.30pm. Later requests are dispatched the following working day.</p><p> </p><p>The majority of DLA &amp; IIDB claims are issued by post and are actioned within a 24 hour period of the request. IIDB Claim forms are also held by 3<sup>rd</sup> party groups such as CAB, Asbestos Support Groups and Solicitors. Customers can also download both IIDB &amp; DLA forms from the Intranet.</p><p> </p><p>The majority of PIP claims are expected to made by telephone unless the claimant is unable to or finds it very difficult to use the phone. In these cases a clerical PIP part 1 would be issued and once the claim is completed and submitted, the PIP part 2 form is system issued overnight.</p><p> </p><p>Income Support New Claims are normally made by telephone, in extraordinary circumstances a contingency process can be invoked to ensure that customer demand is met. Since January 2017 the contingency approach has accounted for 10 % of the total number of new claims made during this period. When this process is used, a claim pack is sent to the customer on the same day as the customer requests it.</p><p> </p><p>All claim forms, with the exception of the PIP part 2 and Income Support claim forms which are issued by 1<sup>st</sup> class post, are issued by 2<sup>nd</sup> class post. The Royal Mail delivery standards for 1<sup>st</sup> class are 93% next day from their receipt by Royal Mail and for second class are 98.5% within 2 days.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T15:56:49.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679170/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679170/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average time is between a claimant requesting by telephone that a  benefit claim form be sent to them by post and their receiving that form.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","61925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679171","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-03","<p>Over the past few months, we have been negotiating new leases with our landlords and partners. This has been a very complex commercial process and has limited our ability for detailed discussions with local customer representative groups on specific site proposals.</p><p>We have committed to a public consultation for offices over three miles and 20 minutes away by public transport and would encourage customer representative groups to submit their views on these proposals via the online consultation.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-03T11:20:43.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679171/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679171/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Department for Work and Pensions: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department has met (a) Citizens Advice Scotland and (b) Money Matters to discuss the current review of his Department's estate.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","61926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679172","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-31","<p>(a) DWP occupies Portcullis House, Glasgow under the Civil Estates Occupancy Agreement (CEOA) as it shares occupation with Her Majesty Customs and Revenue (HMRC) and they hold the lease for this site and therefore DWP does not have this information.</p><p> </p><p>(b) The lease for Corunna House, Glasgow is in the name of Telereal Trillium.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-31T12:08:30.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679172/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679172/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Department for Work and Pensions: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, from which landlord his Department leases (a) Portcullis House, Glasgow and (b) Corunna House, Glasgow.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","61976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679173","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Department previously provided start-up funding to Green Open Homes, with the goal that it should become self-sustaining through industry support. As the Bristol Green Doors report sets out, industry support has been limited so far, which is why Government financing ceased in 2015 as a result.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-03T13:31:23.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679173/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679173/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679173/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-26","Housing: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 23 December 2016 to Question 57830, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his Department's policy on future funding for Green Open Homes of the recommendations in Bristol Green Doors report, Closing Doors on Green Open Homes Events, published in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","61931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679174","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Department’s estimated capital expenditure on projects within the Government Major Projects Portfolio (GMPP) for each of next 5 years is set out in the table below. The annual totals are broken down between Department for Energy and Climate Change (DECC) and Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS), the two former departments which merged in 2016 to create BEIS.</p><p>The estimates are based upon the current composition of the GMPP and their capital costs over the next 5 years. The estimates therefore exclude the capital costs of those major projects that may join the GMPP within the next 5 years.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017/18</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2018/19</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2019/20</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2020/21</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>TOTAL (in millions £)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ex-DECC</p></td><td><p>1590.0</p></td><td><p>1616.0</p></td><td><p>1578.0</p></td><td><p>1610.0</p></td><td><p>1674.0</p></td><td><p>8068.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ex-BIS</p></td><td><p>47.7</p></td><td><p>88.2</p></td><td><p>80.0</p></td><td><p>33.5</p></td><td><p>9.0</p></td><td><p>258.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Combined</p></td><td><p><strong>1637.7</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1704.2</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1658.0</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1643.5</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1683.0</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>8326.4</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-02T15:14:25.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679174/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679174/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679174/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-26","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 26 January 2017 to Question 60573, what estimate he has made of how much his Department will spend on large capital projects in each of the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","61876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679175","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-01","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy’s Europe Directorate employs a dedicated team of officials who work on European policy and negotiations. This includes the arrangements for exit, such as the Great Repeal Bill, and our future relationship with the EU. Officials across the Department also provide advice and analysis on EU exit issues as required.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-01T16:39:16.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679175/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679175/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-26","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 26 January 2017 to Question 60572, whether his Department has a budget for the employment of additional staff to work on the Great Repeal Bill; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","61877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679176","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Government first announced that it was working with the Green Investment Bank (GIB) on options to introduce private capital into GIB in the Autumn Statement 2013.</p><p> </p><p>Since then, Government and GIB have continued to work together to facilitate the introduction of private capital into GIB, including into its offshore wind assets. A two stage auction process for the GIB was formally launched on 3 March 2016, as set out in the Government’s report to Parliament of the same day. The detail of the sale process is commercially confidential.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-02-02T14:41:54.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679176/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679176/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679176/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-26","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 13 January 2017 to Question 59325, on the Green Investment Bank, what other activities have been undertaken by (a) his Department, (b) UK Government Investments and (c) the Green Investment Bank to facilitate the introduction of private capital into that Bank's offshore wind assets.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","61911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679177","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Government recognises the significant contribution that international students bring to the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The UK remains a highly attractive destination for non-EU students, with their numbers remaining at record highs – over 170,000 non-EU entrants to UK HE institutions for the 6th year running. The UK’s success in attracting international students (EU and Non-EU) is reflected in its 10% share of the tertiary international student market in 2014, second only to the US according to the OECD.</p><p> </p><p>The Government promotes study in the UK through the Britain is GREAT marketing campaign and through the British Council, which promotes UK education in over 100 countries, connecting millions of people with the United Kingdom. Government is also promoting UK international success through bilateral engagement on education with overseas partners and through the Chevening and Commonwealth scholarship schemes.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-02-06T14:31:03.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679177/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679177/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-26","Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to address trends in the market share of international students studying in the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","61982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679178","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Government supports expanding the UK’s trading relationship with Iran where it is beneficial for UK businesses and encourages UK businesses to take advantage of the commercial opportunities that arise. As soon as sanctions were lifted, UK Export Finance became the first export credit agency to reintroduce cover for Iran. However, Government and UK Export Finance recognise the difficulties that major UK and international banks face in handling transactions connected to Iran. We are working closely with UK-based banking industry bodies such as the British Bankers’ Association, the Association of Foreign Banks, and with UK-based banks to explore how it can support them as they consider providing financial services to UK businesses who wish to trade with Iran.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-02-03T13:37:46.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679178/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679178/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-26","Exports: Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps UK Export Finance can take to simplify money transactions between the UK and Iran.","false","Biography information for Sir Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","The Cotswolds","Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","61922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679180","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-03","<p>Businesses can make applications from the date the event is published in the TAP programme right up until the cut-off date of 4 weeks prior to the event. The cut-off date is now 4 weeks and changed from 8 weeks in June 2016, to allow flexibility for those who apply late but would benefit from the grant.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-02-03T13:40:20.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679180/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679180/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-26","Tradeshow Access Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps his Department is taking to improve the maximum period of notice businesses receive of acceptance onto the Tradeshow Access Programme to ensure adequate time to prepare promotions at international tradeshows.","false","Biography information for Sir Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","The Cotswolds","Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","61941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679181","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-03","<p>The budget for the Tradeshow Access Programme for 2016/17 was £8 million which was approved in February 2016. The budget for 2017/18 is currently being agreed as part of the DIT Business Forecasting process and will be announced shortly.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-02-03T13:39:00.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679181/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679181/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-26","Tradeshow Access Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the budget is for the Tradeshow Access Programme; and when that budget was approved.","false","Biography information for Sir Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","The Cotswolds","Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","61942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679182","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-03","<p>Since the easing of sanctions in January 2016 the Department for International Trade (DIT) has been working out of the Embassy in Tehran to assist and support UK companies entering the Iranian market.</p><p>DIT and its network of trade advisors across the UK have been raising awareness of the opportunities in Iran, focussing on areas of UK strength such as: aviation, oil and gas, retail, healthcare, infrastructure and financial services.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-02-03T13:36:43.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679182/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679182/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679182/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-26","Overseas Trade: Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the ability of UK businesses to trade with Iran.","false","Biography information for Sir Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","The Cotswolds","Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","61915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679183","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-31","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force.</p><p>The Government will bring forward legislation in the next session that, when enacted, will repeal the European Communities Act 1972 and ensure a functioning statute book on the day we leave.</p><p>This Great Repeal Bill will preserve EU law as it applies on the day we leave, allowing Parliament to make changes to account for the outcome of the exit negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-01-31T13:01:47.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679183/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679183/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679183/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-26","EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether he plans that the Great Repeal Bill will include measures already agreed by the EU but not yet implemented in the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","61974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679295","Department for Education","false","2017-02-10","<p>The Government has a comprehensive framework for safeguarding children, including unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children. In light of the recent increase in arrivals of refugee children into the UK, we have been working with local authorities, non-government organisations and other public bodies to make sure that looked after migrant children receive the immediate support they need.</p><p> </p><p>This support has included making sure local authorities are aware of the heightened risk that they may go missing due to being trafficked. We are also funding the Refugee Council and ECPAT to deliver training for foster carers and support workers of unaccompanied migrant children, who may be at risk of trafficking, to ensure they can also offer the appropriate support to the children in their care.</p><p> </p><p>On 1 November we announced through a written ministerial statement our plans to publish a strategy, by 1 May 2017, for the safeguarding of unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children in England. In developing this strategy, we will consult local authorities to identify any further action that might be taken to prevent these children going missing.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-02-10T12:22:43.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679295/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679295/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679295/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-26","Refugees: Children in Care","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer given by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 25 January (HL Deb, cols 665–6), what assessment they have made of the report in the Independent, on 17 April 2016, of at least 239 refugee children in the UK having disappeared from care facilities in the UK, and the report by ECPAT UK <i>Heading back to harm: A study on trafficked and unaccompanied children going missing from care in the UK</i>, published in November 2016, claiming that from September 2014 to September 2015, 593 unaccompanied asylum-seeking children went missing from care at least once.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL5011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679296","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-06","<p>The last time an Army Division deployed for training purposes was Exercise White Rhino, which took place in West Germany in September 1989. The largest exercise since then was Exercise Saif Sareea II in 2001 when over 22,500 personnel were deployed to Oman.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-06T17:14:32.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679296/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679296/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679296/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-26","Army: Deployment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Earl Howe on 18 January (HL4520), when was the last time the British Army deployed a largely fully formed and supported division into the field for divisional movement and manoeuvre training.","false","Biography information for Earl Attlee",,"Earl Attlee","HL5012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679297","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-09","<p>The UK supports Euratom and is seeking to ensure continuity of co-operation and standards. This Government remains committed to the highest standards of nuclear safety, safeguards and support for the industry.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-09T14:53:39.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679297/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679297/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679297/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-26","EURATOM","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the decision to leave the EU, what will be the UK's future relationship with EURATOM.","false","Biography information for Lord Balfe",,"Lord Balfe","HL5013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679298","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-08","<p>As part of the exit negotiations the Government will discuss with the EU and Member States how best to continue cooperation in the field of medicines regulation in the best interests of both the UK and the EU.<br><br>No decisions have been taken on the future location of the European Medicines Agency. Until we have left the EU, the UK remains a member of the EU with all the rights and obligations that membership entails. The Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency continues to play its full role in all procedures of the EU medicines and devices network as well as other networks.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2017-02-08T15:46:49.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679298/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679298/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679298/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-26","European Medicines Agency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the UK's exit from the EU, whether the UK will leave the European Medicines Agency; and if so, when the Agency will be relocated away from the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Balfe",,"Lord Balfe","HL5014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679299","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-09","<p>The European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) is an international organisation and not an EU institution. The UK’s exit from the EU should not therefore impact on our membership of the EBRD, nor should it have any bearing on the Bank’s headquarters being located in London, which is enshrined in the EBRD’s Articles of Agreement.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-02-09T12:11:55.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679299/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679299/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679299/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-26","European Bank for Reconstruction and Development","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the UK's exit from the EU, whether the UK will cease to be a full member of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development; and if so, when the Bank will relocate away from the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Balfe",,"Lord Balfe","HL5015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679300","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-09","<p>The European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF) is an independent intergovernmental treaty organisation including both EU and non-EU member and co-operating states. There are no plans for the UK to cease to be a member of ECMWF and we remain committed to hosting the organisation in the UK.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-09T13:12:35.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679300/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679300/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679300/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-26","European Centre for Medium Range Weather Forecasts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the UK's exit from the EU, whether the UK will cease to participate in the European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts; and if so, when the Centre will relocate away from the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Balfe",,"Lord Balfe","HL5016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679301","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-08","<p>The future structure of UK and European Union regulatory frameworks for the financial sector are a matter for the withdrawal negotiations and future policy development.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-02-08T15:59:46.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679301/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679301/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679301/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-26","European Banking Authority","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the UK's exit from the EU, whether the UK will leave the European Banking Authority; and if so, when the Banking Authority will relocate away from the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Balfe",,"Lord Balfe","HL5017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679302","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-09","<p>The planned recruitment of 2,500 new prison officers and estimated 5,500 replacements relates to public sector prison staff.</p><p> </p><p>Private providers are required to maintain a sufficient number of staff, with the requisite level of skill and experience to ensure that the Prison is safe, secure and decent environment. We are engaging with private providers on how the new staffing model outlined in the Prison Safety and Reform White Paper will be implemented in private prisons.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-09T17:02:07.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679302/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679302/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679302/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-26","Prison Officers: Recruitment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether their planned recruitment of prison staff includes staff for private prisons as well as public sector prisons; and if so, how many will be recruited for each sector.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL5018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679304","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-01","<p>Highways England expected junctions 16 to 19 of the M1 motorway to be fully operational as a smart motorway by the end of March 2017. However, it is likely this will now be delayed and a revised date will be advised in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The overall M1 junctions 13 to 19 scheme will still be completed within Highways England’s Delivery Plan target of 2021-2022.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-02-01T15:08:17.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679304/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679304/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679304/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-26","M1","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect junctions 16 to 19 of the M1 motorway to be fully operational.","false","Biography information for Lord Blunkett",,"Lord Blunkett","HL5019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679305","Home Office","false","2017-02-09","<p>The Home Office has received no recent representations on this subject.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-09T13:58:50.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679305/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679305/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679305/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-26","Police: Bureaucracy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what recent representations they have received on the amount of time spent by police officers on paperwork each year.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL5020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679306","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Government takes the protection of individuals’ personal data online as well as offline, seriously. The Information Commissioner is the UK's independent authority responsible for administering and enforcing information rights and provides guidance and advice to individuals and organisations on, among other things, the protection of personal data online. The Information Commissioner’s Office has a number of tools at its disposal to take action against those that breach the legislation. These powers include the ability to conduct audits, serve enforcement notices and impose civil monetary penalties of up to £500,000.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recently announced it would be implementing the forthcoming General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) by May 2018. Amongst other protections offered, the GDPR provides individuals with increased control over how their personal data is collected and used online.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2017-02-06T14:34:25.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679306/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679306/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679306/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-26","Data Protection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to help people protect their personal data online.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL5021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679307","Department for Education","false","2017-02-08","<p>The Department for Education publish <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-neet" target="_blank">Quarterly statistics on young people not in education, employment or training (NEET)</a> from the Labour Force Survey (LFS). The data covers England and is based on academic age. Many 19 year olds will be academic age 18 so academic ages 16-18 are included in the answer below.</p><p>Statistics for Quarter 4 2016 will be published on 23<sup>rd</sup> February 2017. Trends should be assessed by comparing the current time period with the same time period in the previous year to account for seasonal effects. Figures are therefore provided for the latest 2 years below.</p><p>It should also be noted that sample sizes in the Labour Force Survey are small for individual age cohorts, so sampling variation is large and caution should be taken in interpreting changes over the short term, particularly when numbers are small such as 16 and 17 year olds NEET.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="3"><p>Academic age</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Total 16-18</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>16-18 NEET rate</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 Q4</p></td><td><p>15,000</p></td><td><p>34,000</p></td><td><p>84,000</p></td><td><p>133,000</p></td><td><p>7.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 Q1</p></td><td><p>10,000</p></td><td><p>37,000</p></td><td><p>88,000</p></td><td><p>134,000</p></td><td><p>7.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 Q2</p></td><td><p>14,000</p></td><td><p>48,000</p></td><td><p>80,000</p></td><td><p>142,000</p></td><td><p>7.5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 Q3</p></td><td><p>28,000</p></td><td><p>81,000</p></td><td><p>82,000</p></td><td><p>191,000</p></td><td><p>10.2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 Q4</p></td><td><p>12,000</p></td><td><p>28,000</p></td><td><p>81,000</p></td><td><p>122,000</p></td><td><p>6.6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016 Q1</p></td><td><p>20,000</p></td><td><p>35,000</p></td><td><p>65,000</p></td><td><p>121,000</p></td><td><p>6.5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016 Q2</p></td><td><p>25,000</p></td><td><p>52,000</p></td><td><p>74,000</p></td><td><p>151,000</p></td><td><p>8.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016 Q3</p></td><td><p>30,000</p></td><td><p>64,000</p></td><td><p>71,000</p></td><td><p>164,000</p></td><td><p>8.7%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The NEET rate for the 16-18 age group overall was 8.7% at the end of Q3 2016, 1.5 percentage points lower than Q3 2015 and the lowest Q3 NEET rate since consistent records began in 2000.</p><p>The ONS also release <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peoplenotinwork/unemployment/datasets/youngpeoplenotineducationemploymentortrainingneettable1" target="_blank">quarterly NEET estimates</a> but their figures cover the UK, are based on calendar age and are seasonally adjusted.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-02-08T17:48:56.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679307/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679307/answer","HL5022 Attachment.xls","Quarterly NEET Estimates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679307/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-26","Young People: Unemployment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many young people aged between 16 and 19 years of age were not in education, employment or training in each quarter of 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL5022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679308","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-06","<p>Intake figures to the Army Reserve during the calendar year 2016 are currently being validated ahead of publication as official statistics on 9 February 2017.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-06T17:13:45.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679308/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679308/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679308/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-26","Army Reserve: Recruitment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many soldiers were recruited to the Army Reserve in 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL5023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679309","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-09","<p>Monthly generation estimates are not available; however, the latest available quarterly estimates are published in <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/energy-trends-section-6-renewables" target="_blank">Energy Trends table 6.1</a>:</p><p><strong>UK electricity generation from onshore wind, Apr-Jun 2016 and Jul-Sep 2016<sup>(1)(2)</sup></strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>GWh</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2016 Q2 (Apr-Jun)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016 Q3 (Jul-Sep)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Onshore Wind electricity generation</p></td><td><p>4,028</p></td><td><p>4,566</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Energy Trends 6.1, December 2016, available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/energy-trends-section-6-renewables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/energy-trends-section-6-renewables</a></p><p>(1) Generation figures for the latest quarter are provisional.</p><p>(2) Actual generation figures are given where available. Otherwise they are estimated using a typical load factor or the design load factor, where known. Generation from Feed-in Tariff schemes is estimated this way.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-09T14:32:59.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679309/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679309/answer","Renewables.pdf","Energy Trends 6.1","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679309/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-26","Wind Power","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate of the amount of electricity generated by onshore wind farms in each of the last six months.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL5024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679310","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-09","<p>The Government does not hold data on new jobs created in each of the last five years that requires a university degree.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-09T13:13:50.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679310/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679310/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679310/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-26","Job Creation: Graduates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate of the proportion of new jobs created in each of the last five years which required a university degree.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL5025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679311","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-31","<p>The latest available estimates show that the UK ran a trade balance (a) with France of –£6.1 billion in 2014 and -£5.2 billion in 2015; (b) with Germany of –£24.7 billion in 2014 and -£25.3 billion in 2015 and (c) with Italy of -£4.8 billion in 2014 and -£3.9 billion in 2015. Data is currently unavailable for 2016.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-01-31T14:57:23.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679311/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679311/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679311/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-26","Balance of Trade","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in (1) 2014, (2) 2015, and (3) 2016, what were the balance of trade figures between the UK and (a) France, (b) Germany, and (c) Italy.","false","Biography information for Lord Hoyle",,"Lord Hoyle","HL5026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679312","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-09","<p>Authorised Economic Operator (AEO) status is an internationally recognised quality mark indicating that a trader’s role in the international supply chain is secure, and that their customs controls and procedures are efficient and compliant. AEO status is not mandatory for businesses, but it gives quicker access to certain simplified customs procedures and in some cases the right to ‘fast-track’ shipments through some customs and safety and security procedures.</p><p>AEO status was introduced across the EU in 2008. Some EU countries decided to make AEO status mandatory – both to maintain a current customs authorisation and to apply for a wider range of customs authorisations. This decision is likely to have increased interest in obtaining AEO status in those countries. In the UK we chose not to mandate the link between customs authorisations and AEO status, which allowed UK businesses to continue to enjoy current facilitations and, when appropriate, apply for new customs authorisations, without having to undergo the sometimes lengthy AEO authorisation process. For those UK businesses who choose and are eligible to obtain AEO status additional facilitations and benefits are available.</p><p>The UK Government is currently exploring options to simplify customs procedures, including opportunities to streamline the AEO authorisation process and provide additional benefits.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-02-09T17:22:51.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679312/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679312/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679312/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-26","Overseas Trade","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why only 530 UK companies have Authorised Economic Operator Status, compared to 6,000 in Germany, 1,500 in Holland, and 1,400 in France; and what steps they are taking to increase that number.","false","Biography information for Lord Inglewood",,"Lord Inglewood","HL5027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679313","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-09","<p>Companies relocate operations for many different commercial reasons.</p><p>Since the UK voted to leave the EU, we have worked closely with firms across the country to understand their plans and make clear our commitment to a bold and ambitious free trade agreement with the EU that removes as many barriers to trade as possible. Companies such as GlaxoSmithKline, Nissan and Apple have announced major investments in the UK since the referendum.</p><p>In the event of redundancies, the Government looks to support affected workers back into employment via the Rapid Response Service. We closely monitor major job losses and will look to provide bespoke support if required.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-09T13:13:35.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679313/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679313/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679313/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-26","Multinational Companies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many companies have announced a relocation of (1) all, or (2) part of, their operations from the UK, following the announcement that the UK will leave the single market; and what additional support is being provided for British workers who lose their jobs as a result of such relocations.","false","Biography information for Baroness Janke",,"Baroness Janke","HL5028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679315","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-03","<p>The most recent figures for the percentage of gross domestic product spent on defence for each NATO member state were published in July 2016 and can be found in table 3 of the attached.</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nato.int/nato_static_fl2014/assets/pdf/pdf_2016_07/20160704_160704-pr2016-116.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.nato.int/nato_static_fl2014/assets/pdf/pdf_2016_07/20160704_160704-pr2016-116.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Under this Government there are no published figures available for future NATO defence spending, however the UK is committed to meet our NATO pledge to spend 2 per cent of GDP on defence every year of this decade in accordance with the NATO guidelines.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-03T14:44:08.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679315/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679315/answer","20160704_160704-pr2016-116.pdf","Defence Expenditures of NATO Countries (2009-16)","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679315/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-26","Defence: Expenditure","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are the most recent figures for the percentage of gross domestic product spent on defence for each NATO member state; and where figures are available, what those percentages are expected to be in two years' time.","false","Biography information for Lord Jopling",,"Lord Jopling","HL5029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679316","Leader of the House of Lords","false","2017-02-08","<p>As detailed in my previous answer (HL4521), I have recently written to Lord Keen of Elie QC and the Secretary of State for Justice to make clear the House’s expectations with regards to Questions for Written Answer. I am informed that the Ministry of Justice has taken steps to rectify the issue, including making further process improvements, for example reducing the internal deadlines to allow more time for clearance. Lord Keen of Elie QC has also had discussions with senior officials within the Department about its recent performance. The Ministry of Justice has now cleared all overdue Questions for Written Answer, including HL3278, which was answered on 30 January 2017.</p><p>My office will continue to work with all departments to ensure prompt and satisfactory answers to Questions for Written Answer.</p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park",,"2017-02-08T17:44:21.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679316/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679316/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679316/answer",,,,,"92",,"Leader of the House of Lords","2017-01-26","Ministry of Justice: Written Questions","2","House of Lords","To ask the Leader of the House, further to her Written Answer on 23 January (HL4521), whether the shortage of resources within the Ministry of Justice will be resolved in time for the outstanding Question for Written Answer tabled on 16 November (HL3278) to be answered before the end of February.","false","Biography information for Lord Jopling",,"Lord Jopling","HL5030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679317","Department for Education","false","2017-02-10","<p>Departmental advice on the School Food Standards, which includes the requirements for milk, is attached and available on Gov.uk. A summary of the standards and a practical guide are available from the School Food Plan website.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Governing boards are legally responsible for meeting t</strong>he School Food Standards.</p><p>From previous surveys of compliance against the previous standards, we are confident that almost all schools are following the new standards appropriately.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-02-10T14:24:05.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679317/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679317/answer","School_food_in_England.pdf","School_Food_in_England","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679317/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-26","School Milk","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answers by Lord Nash on 25 January (HL Deb, cols 662–3), what guidance has been provided to primary and secondary schools to ensure compliance with the milk requirements of the standards for school food in England, published on 9 September 2016; and how schools are required to demonstrate that they have complied with those requirements.","false","Biography information for Lord Lexden",,"Lord Lexden","HL5031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679318","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-09","<p>The government will publish a response to its consultation on transposing the EU Fourth Money Laundering Directive, shortly. It will include a draft of the new Money Laundering Regulations and will be open for a four week consultation. The draft regulations will reflect government positions on a number of policies including whether gambling service providers are exempt from the directives requirements.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-02-09T14:53:20.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679318/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679318/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679318/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-26","Money Laundering: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they intend to announce their policy with regard to the implementation of the EU Fourth Anti-Money Laundering Directive; and what assessment they have made of its impact on the bookmaking sector.","true","Biography information for Lord Lipsey",,"Lord Lipsey","HL5032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679319","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-09","<p>The industrial strategy is an opportunity to make the most of the diverse strengths of all of the UK’s cities and regions, including rural areas. Government is already taking a range of steps to improve productivity in rural areas, for example through investment in digital infrastructure. Our industrial strategy Green Paper seeks views on how we can take further steps to drive improved productivity in growth in all parts of the country, including rural areas.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-09T15:49:36.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679319/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679319/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679319/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-26","Industry: Rural Areas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact on rural areas of the proposed Industrial Strategy.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering",,"Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","HL5033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679320","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Government is committed to commencing section 67 of the Serious Crime Act 2015 and will do so as soon as possible.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-07T15:11:41.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679320/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679320/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679320/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-26","Offences against Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect to bring section 67 of the Serious Crime Act 2015 into force.","false","Biography information for Lord Paddick",,"Lord Paddick","HL5034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679321","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-08","<p>The total statistical value in sterling for industrial goods outside of the EU was £337,197,217,084.94. The total of Customs duties collected was £2,321,736,536.64 and the VAT duties collected on those goods was £20,844,769,400.38 in 2015.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-02-08T15:59:24.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679321/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679321/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679321/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-26","Industrial Products: Imports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government in 2015 what was the value in sterling of (1) UK imports from outside the EU of industrial goods, and (2) UK customs duties charged and collected by HM Revenue and Customs on those imports.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL5035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679322","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-09","<p>The total value in sterling for imports of Agricultural goods and Fish products from outside of the EU was £12,377,442,495.75.The total value of Customs duties collected on those goods was £408,379,330.90 and the VAT duties collected was £282,733,876.80 in 2015.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-02-09T12:11:05.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679322/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679322/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679322/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-26","Agricultural and Fish Products: Imports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government in 2015 what was the value in sterling of (1) UK imports from outside the EU of agricultural and fish products, and (2) UK customs duties collected by HM Revenue and Customs on those imports.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL5036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679323","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-09","<p>The proportion of aggregated value in sterling of UK imports of agricultural and fish products with a zero rate of duty, from outside the EU, was 38.32% and for industrial products with a zero rate of duty was 23.33%.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-02-09T12:11:20.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679323/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679323/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679323/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-26","Import Duties","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government in 2015 what proportion of the aggregated value in sterling of UK imports of industrial goods and agricultural and fish products bore zero-rate customs duties.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL5037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679324","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-09","<p>Euratom provides the legal framework for civil nuclear power generation and radioactive waste management across the European Union. Specifically, it covers nuclear safeguards, and the movement and trade of nuclear materials between Member States and third countries.</p><p> </p><p>This Government remains committed to the highest standards of nuclear safety, safeguards and support for the industry.Whilst membership of Euratom has served the UK well, the benefits of Euratom membership can be achieved through other means as well.</p><p> </p><p>The UK will remain publicly accountable on nuclear safety matters through our membership of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). The IAEA’s legal frameworks for the nuclear sector are the basis on which the Euratom Community and the UK’s own domestic regime is based; there is no intention to weaken the current standards. The UK’s future nuclear safeguards arrangements will continue to provide the quality, safety and robustness that currently exist under Euratom.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-09T14:52:54.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679324/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679324/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679324/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-26","EURATOM","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what services, provisions or assistance are provided to the UK as a result of the UK's membership of the European Atomic Energy Community, EURATOM; and in the event of the UK withdrawing from the EU, how any such benefits will be affected or replaced.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL5038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679325","Department for Education","false","2017-02-01","<p>The Government does not hold information on the number of cases of homophobic bullying recorded in schools, as the recording of instances of bullying is managed locally by schools. Nonetheless, we are examining the overall prevalence of a range of types of bullying, including homophobic, biphobic, and transphobic bullying, through surveys such as the National Foundation for Educational Research (NFER) Teacher Voice and the Pupil and Parent/Carer omnibus surveys, which will report later this year.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to promoting LGB&amp;T equality, including amongst young people. We are currently investing £2.8 million in a three-year programme to prevent and address homophobic, biphobic and transphobic bullying in schools.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-02-01T15:25:46.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679325/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679325/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679325/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-26","Schools: Homophobia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many cases there have been of homophobic bullying recorded in schools in each of the last three years; and what plans they have, if any, to increase awareness of LGBT rights amongst young people.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679326","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-09","<p>Sexual discrimination is not a prosecutable offence.</p><p> </p><p>Employment tribunals are not criminal courts and therefore it is not possible to prosecute for unlawful sexual discrimination before an employment tribunal.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-09T17:00:31.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679326/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679326/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679326/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-26","Gender: Discrimination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many prosecutions have been brought for unlawful sexual discrimination in the field of employment in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679327","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-02","<p>One person without a home is one too many and we are committed to doing all we can to prevent homelessness. This government is determined to help the most vulnerable in society, which is why we're investing £550 million until 2020 to tackle homelessness and rough sleeping.</p><p>As part of this, in December we announced 84 successful bids to our £50 million Homelessness Prevention Programme. This will help those people at risk of becoming homeless, already sleeping rough or those with complex needs, to get back on their feet.</p><p>We are going even further and changing the law by backing Bob Blackman MP's Homelessness Reduction Bill. This will mean that people across the country get the help they need to avoid becoming homeless in the first place.</p><p>DCLG publishes annual statistics on the number of people seen sleeping rough on a single night in England by local authority. These are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics</a></p><p>As Housing is a devolved matter, rough sleeping statistics for Wales are available here:</p><p><a href="https://statswales.gov.wales/Catalogue/Housing/Homelessness/Rough-Sleepers" target="_blank">https://statswales.gov.wales/Catalogue/Housing/Homelessness/Rough-Sleepers</a></p><p>Rough sleeping statistics for Scotland can be found here:</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.scot/Topics/Statistics/Browse/Housing-Regeneration/RefTables" target="_blank">http://www.gov.scot/Topics/Statistics/Browse/Housing-Regeneration/RefTables</a></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-02-02T13:50:02.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679327/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679327/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679327/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-26","Sleeping Rough","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many rough sleepers there were in the UK for each of the last three years; and what plans they have to tackle this issue.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679328","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-01","<p>The Department for Transport and the Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) work with a wide range of partners, including the British Airline Pilots' Association and the Police, to ensure our understanding of potential hazards to aircraft remains up to date. Work is underway to better understand the risk posed by drones to commercial aircraft and ensure that the regulatory and industry responses remain fit for purpose. We continue to develop proposals which we will put forward in the near future, and in December 2016 the Government launched a consultation to determine if further measures are needed in this area.</p><p> </p><p>We have also been working closely with the CAA and industry to adapt and strengthen regulations and implement mitigations as drones use and the related technology evolves. This has led to a new safety awareness campaign aimed at leisure drone users. So far, this has included the launch of a new www.dronesafe.uk website, a #400ftBritain drone photography competition that highlights safety rules, and a free new app ‘Drone Assist’ by NATS, which shows users where they should and should not fly in their locality.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-02-01T15:01:35.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679328/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679328/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679328/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-26","Unmanned Air Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what measures they are taking to improve the safety of drones and to reduce the likelihood of collisions with aircraft, pending the outcome of the current consultation on the safe use of drones.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL5042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679329","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-07","<p>The independent UK Airprox Board (UKAB) is responsible for assessing reported airprox in the interests of enhancing air safety. Reports of all airprox events are published on the UKAB website <a href="https://www.airproxboard.org.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.airproxboard.org.uk/</a>.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016 there were 70 reported airprox incidents involving drones, the locations of which are summarised below and further details are included in the attached table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Location</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of reported airprox incidents involving drones</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London Heathrow</p></td><td><p>25</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London Gatwick</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Manchester Airport</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London City</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London Stansted</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Morton-in-Marsh</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Odiham</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>70</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-02-07T12:53:22.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679329/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679329/answer","HL5043 - List of reported airprox incidents involving drones in 2016.docx","HL5043 - Table with further information ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679329/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-26","Unmanned Air Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many reports of drone related incidents involving aircraft were made last year; and what was the location of each of those incidents.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL5043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679330","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Government engages regularly with airport operators and airlines to discuss a range of safety and security issues, including the threat posed by drones. For instance, in November 2016 the Airport Operators Association chaired a meeting between its members and Government on the risks related to drones.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-02-07T14:06:44.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679330/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679330/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679330/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-26","Unmanned Air Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with airport operators and airlines about measures to reduce the risks to aircraft from the use of drones.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL5044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679331","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-07","<p>On 22 December, Department for Communities and Local Government Officials wrote to Local Authority Chief Executives in London, Surrey, Sussex, Kent and Hampshire and Local Resilience Forum Chairs in London, Kent, Surrey, Sussex, Hampshire and Isle of Wight, to request support for contingency plans aimed at minimising disruption for passengers as a result of the industrial action affecting Southern rail train services, in particular the ASLEF strike planned for the week commencing 9<sup>th</sup> January.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has not provided additional funding to local authorities specific to the request from the Department for Communities and Local Government for support to minimise disruption as a result of strikes on Southern Rail and were not asked for funding.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-02-07T13:35:56.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679331/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679331/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679331/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-26","Southern: Strikes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what funding they have provided to support local authorities asked by the Department for Communities and Local Government on 22 December 2016 to take action to support contingency plans to minimise disruption as a result of strikes on Southern Rail.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL5045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679332","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-09","<p>We are increasing awareness of Access to Work among employers through a range of communications, including using the Disability Confident campaign to provide information to employer organisations. Planned communications activity includes direct e-mail marketing to employers and employer associations, employer engagement at a national level through Jobcentre Plus National Employer and Partnership Team, and proactive local engagement through Jobcentre Plus partnerships managers, Disability Employment Advisers and employer advisers. We are also working closely with Remploy, who operate the Mental Health Support Service, to maximise opportunities to promote the service to employers.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2017-02-09T15:48:55.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679332/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679332/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679332/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Access to Work Programme","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they intend to increase awareness of Access to Work among employers.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL5046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679333","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-08","<p>To become a Disability Confident Employer, an employer will need to test their business against a set of statements, and commit to take certain actions. As Disability Confident Employers move through towards becoming a ‘Disability Confident Leader’, they will need to put their assessment up for external challenge. These external validations could be done by a professional assessment body, a disabled user led organisation, a disabled staff forum, an existing DC Leader, or a combination of these. They will also need to take on a role working with other employers to encourage and support them to follow their own Disability Confident journeys.</p><p> </p><p>When employers sign up as Disability Confident they are asked to make specific meaningful offers for disabled people such as jobs, apprenticeships, internships, and work experience. Jobcentre Plus staff will be working with the Disability Confident employers in their localities to develop these offers into opportunities for local disabled people.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2017-02-08T16:19:45.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679333/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679333/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679333/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-26","Employment: Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to develop a review process for Disability Confident to ensure businesses are meeting their commitments.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL5047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679334","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-09","<p>The timetable for the development of Sizewell C is a matter for the developer EDF Energy. EDF Energy is currently consulting publicly on its proposals for this site.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-09T14:51:44.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679334/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679334/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679334/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-26","Sizewell C Power Station","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect to make a decision as to whether to proceed with the second nuclear power station in a generation at Sizewell.","true","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL5048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679335","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-07","<p>The A130 is a local road and its management is the responsibility of the local highways authority – in this instance Essex County Council. I understand that the section you are referring to has been coned off after issues were discovered during routine inspections. The additional lanes have been completed but remain coned off after a routine inspection highlighted issues with crash barriers along the route.</p><p> </p><p>Further investigation work over recent months has revealed a need to reconstruct the ground alongside the carriageway as a preventative measure to protect against the risk of slippage in the long-term.</p><p> </p><p>I understand work to resolve these issues is due to begin in March.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-02-07T13:36:18.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679335/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679335/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/679335/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-26","A130","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are the purposes and plans for the coned off carriageway of the A130 trunk road between the A12 and the A13.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL5049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678512","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Government is committed to a democracy that works for everyone in which every voice matters. It is important that young people are engaged in the democratic process and participate in our wider political dialogue.</p><p>The Government remains in favour of maintaining the current voting age and has no plans to lower it.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-01-30T10:50:07.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678512/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678512/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678512/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-25","Voting Rights: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his policies of National Youth Parliament's Votes at 16 campaign.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","61609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678513","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-01-30T10:46:12.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678513/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678513/answer","PQ 61643_final  .pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Average Salary","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678513/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-25","Average Earnings: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the average salary for (a) men and (b) women was in (i) Greater London and (ii) the London borough of Newham in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","61643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678514","Home Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>I am responsible for the policy and operations related to asylum seekers and refugees inside the UK. The primary responsibility for refugees outside the UK rests with the host country within which they are residing; this principle applies to Syrian refugees who have entered mainland Europe.</p><p> </p><p>However, the UK has a strong interest in this matter, and, as with refugees issues further afield, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, Home Office and Department for International Development work closely to support Europe in dealing with refugees, including those from Syria. We have:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Provided significant assistance via the European Asylum Support Office to Member States facing particular pressures to ensure that all refugees can have effective access to protection, wherever they are.</li></ul><ul><li>Established a £10 million Refugee Children’s Fund for Europe, which aims to prevent and mitigate protection risks faced by vulnerable separated and unaccompanied refugee and migrant children in Europe.</li><li>Allocated up to £34 million to the humanitarian response in Greece.</li></ul><p>This is in addition to the UK’s wider response to the Syrian crisis. We have pledged £2.3 billion, making the UK one of the largest donors to the humanitarian crisis.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-30T16:05:18.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678514/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678514/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678514/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-25","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 24 January 2017 to Question 60854, to which Minister in which Department hon. Members should address their concerns on the well-being of Syrian refugees who have entered mainland Europe.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","61657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678515","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-02","<p>Following the departure of the previous Chief Scientific Adviser to the Treasury in November 2016, the Treasury expects to appoint a new Chief Scientific Adviser in due course.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-02-02T14:29:09.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678515/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678515/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678515/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-25","Treasury: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether there is a vacancy for a Chief Scientific Advisor to the Treasury.","true","Biography information for Stephen Metcalfe","South Basildon and East Thurrock","Stephen Metcalfe","61709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678516","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-01","<p>Any healthcare provider which is a charity and using their property wholly or mainly for charitable purposes will be entitled to 80% mandatory rate relief. Charities in the healthcare sector make an important contribution to our society and it is right they should benefit from mandatory rate relief.</p><p>NHS properties, like almost all other buildings occupied by public bodies, have been subject to non-domestic rates since they were introduced. Operational costs related to property are taken into account at spending reviews in determining the overall level of funding for the NHS.</p><p>A £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme will provide support for the minority of properties which face an increase in rates as a result of the 2017 revaluation, and applies equally to public bodies such as the NHS.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","61562","2017-02-01T15:02:41.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678516/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678516/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678516/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Health Services: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the reasons are for business rate relief (a) being provided to private health companies and (b) not being provided to publicly funded health services.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","61561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678517","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-01","<p>Any healthcare provider which is a charity and using their property wholly or mainly for charitable purposes will be entitled to 80% mandatory rate relief. Charities in the healthcare sector make an important contribution to our society and it is right they should benefit from mandatory rate relief.</p><p>NHS properties, like almost all other buildings occupied by public bodies, have been subject to non-domestic rates since they were introduced. Operational costs related to property are taken into account at spending reviews in determining the overall level of funding for the NHS.</p><p>A £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme will provide support for the minority of properties which face an increase in rates as a result of the 2017 revaluation, and applies equally to public bodies such as the NHS.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","61561","2017-02-01T15:02:41.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678517/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678517/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678517/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","NHS: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he has made an assessment of the effect of the level of business rates on NHS budgets.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","61562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678518","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-30","<p>The arrangements for withdrawal from the EU, including from the budget, will be a matter for the withdrawal agreement as part of the Article 50 process.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-01-30T10:47:13.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678518/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678518/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678518/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-25","EU Budget: Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 23 January 2017 to Question 60692, on EU budget: contributions, whether funding commitments made by the Government to the EU as a final settlement, once negotiations on the UK leaving the EU are complete, will not be funded so as to acquire new debt.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","61541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678519","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-02","<p>The tax revenues (Offshore Corporation Tax and Petroleum Revenue Tax) arising from the production and extraction of North Sea oil and gas from the UK and UK Continental Shelf are presented in HM Revenue and Customs receipts publication (latest version December 2016), which is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/584766/Dec16_Receipts_Table_Final.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/584766/Dec16_Receipts_Table_Final.xlsx</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-02T16:29:14.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678519/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678519/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678519/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-25","Fossil Fuels: Tax Yields","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the contribution of UK continental shelf oil and gas to the annual tax yield.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","61788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678520","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Government will want to consider the future of all programmes that are currently EU funded, once we have left the EU. Leaving the EU means we will want to take our own decisions about how to deliver the policy objectives previously targeted by EU funding. Over the coming months, we will consult closely with stakeholders to review all EU funding schemes in the round, to ensure that any on-going funding commitments best serve the UK's national interest, while ensuring appropriate investor certainty.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2017-01-30T16:59:12.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678520/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678520/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678520/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his policy is on continuing regional aid funding at the same levels currently provided by the EU after 2020; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","61759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678521","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Chancellor's guarantee on EU funds means that the Government will honour projects agreed before the UK leaves the EU, even when they continue beyond Brexit. The Government will want to consider the future of all programmes that are currently EU funded, once we have left the EU. Leaving the EU means we will want to take our own decisions about how to deliver the policy objectives previously targeted by EU funding. Over the coming months, we will consult closely with stakeholders to review all EU funding schemes in the round, to ensure that any on-going funding commitments best serve the UK's national interest, while ensuring appropriate investor certainty.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2017-01-30T16:55:03.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678521/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678521/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678521/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","EU Grants and Loans: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the total amount of regional aid funding for the West Midlands from EU sources which will be discontinued when the UK leaves the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","61760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678522","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-30","<p>The planning system already contains strong protections for sites of archaeological interest. These protections will apply to measures introduced by the Housing and Planning Act.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-30T16:43:48.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678522/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678522/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678522/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Archaeological Sites: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to use the provisions of the Housing and Planning Act 2016 to protect sites of archaeological interest subject to development.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","61763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678523","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-30","<p>The planning conditions measure in the Neighbourhood Planning Bill will not restrict the ability of local planning authorities to propose conditions that are necessary to achieve sustainable development, in line with the National Planning Policy Framework.</p><p>Where a pre-commencement condition is required to address archaeological considerations and meets the tests for conditions set out in national policy, then the authority can impose such a condition, with the agreement of the applicant. In the unlikely event that an applicant refuses to agree to such a pre-commencement condition being imposed, the local planning authority can refuse planning permission.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-30T16:44:47.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678523/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678523/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678523/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Archaeological Sites: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, for what reasons pre-commencement conditions have been removed from planning applications relating to archaeological considerations on a site due for development; and what alternative protections will be put in place to protect such sites.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","61764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678524","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-02","<p>Swindon Borough Council has received the following amounts in New Homes Bonus in each year since its inception:</p><p>Year 1 (2011-12): £1,451,214<br>Year 2 (2012-13): £2,783,259<br>Year 3 (2013-14): £4,005,405 <br>Year 4 (2014-15): £5,074,524<br>Year 5 (2015-16): £6,102,568<br>Year 6 (2016-17): £7,007,604</p><p>The total amount of New Homes Bonus which has been awarded to Local Authorities since its inception is:</p><p>Year 1 (2011-12): £ 199,260,649<br>Year 2 (2012-13): £ 431,890,216<br>Year 3 (2013-14): £ 668,339,313 <br>Year 4 (2014-15): £ 916,973,547<br>Year 5 (2015-16): £ 1,167,637,982 <br>Year 6 (2016-17): £ 1,461,855,324</p><p>I will place a table that shows how much New Homes Bonus has been received by all local authorities in each year since the inception of this funding, in the Library of the House.</p><p><strong><strong> </strong></strong></p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-02-02T16:28:08.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678524/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678524/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678524/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much New Homes Bonus funding has been received by (a) Swindon Borough Council and (b) all local authorities in each year since the inception of that funding.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","61781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678525","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-02","<p>By the end of the Parliament, local government will retain 100% of taxes raised locally, giving councils control of around an additional £12.5 billion of business rates to spend on local services. In order to ensure that the reforms are fiscally neutral, these new powers will come with additional responsibilities, as well as phasing out some grants from Whitehall. This move towards self-sufficiency and away from dependence on central government is something councils have long campaigned for. There were over 450 responses to the Government’s summer consultation. My officials are currently considering all responses and we will publish a summary of the responses and our proposals for the broad way forward shortly.</p><p>On 13 January 2017 we introduced the Local Government Finance Bill that will establish the framework for the reformed system. All relevant documents can be found here: <a href="http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2016-17/localgovernmentfinance.html" target="_blank">http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2016-17/localgovernmentfinance.html</a>. We will continue to work closely with local government during the passage of the legislation, to shape the detail of the reforms.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-02T13:55:28.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678525/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678525/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678525/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678525/answer/previousversion/33000","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to publish the summary of responses to his Department's consultation on 100 per cent business rates retention; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","61797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678526","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-02","<p>By the end of the Parliament, local government will retain 100 per cent of taxes raised locally, giving councils control of around an additional £12.5 billion of business rates to spend on local services. Councils have long campaigned for this move towards local self-sufficiency. In order that these reforms are revenue neutral, local authorities will have £12.5 billion of additional responsibilities delegated to them. We consulted last Summer on these reforms, including on which additional functions should be delegated, and had over 450 responses. My officials are currently considering all responses and we will publish a summary of the responses and our proposals for the broad way forward in due course.</p><p>If public health responsibilities were to be resourced through retained business rates, then this would change the funding mechanism by which the resource is supplied to local authorities, but would not change the legal requirements on local authorities to improve public health.</p><p>The legislative framework for public health would remain, including regulations mandating particular services. If public health responsibilities were to be resourced through retained business rates then the Government would also consider whether any adjustments to this framework are necessary, and if required the Government would consult on any proposed changes.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","61637 ; 61687 ; 61691","2017-02-02T14:40:08.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678526/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678526/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678526/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Public Health: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of devolution of the public health grant and 100 per cent business rates retention on local authorities' delivery of the public health outcomes framework from 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","61774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678528","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Government will confirm the details of the 100 per cent Business Rates Retention pilots alongside the final local government finance settlement.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-02T13:54:05.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678528/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678528/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678528/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678528/answer/previousversion/32995","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to publish details of the pilot schemes for 100 per cent business rates retention; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","61588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678529","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-30","<p>According to the department's English Housing Survey, in 2014-15, 27% of first time buyers had help from friends and family to purchase their home. One in ten used an inheritance.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-30T16:56:57.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678529/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678529/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","First Time Buyers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what data his Department holds on the extent to which first-time home buyers receive financial help from their parents or another family member.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","61589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678530","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-02","<p>The information is not collected by the department.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-02T13:51:44.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678530/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678530/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678530/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Social Workers: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the retention rate is for newly-qualified social workers who were recorded in service in each year from November 2010 to November 2015; and how many such social workers entered service in that time period.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","61564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678531","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-01","<p>The Government has introduced changes to the New Homes Bonus to sharpen the incentive effect of the Bonus to increase the delivery of new homes, whilst freeing up resources to be recycled within the local government settlement to support authorities with particular pressures in adult social care. We chose to take a moderate approach from the options we consulted on and to stage the changes to give authorities time to adapt their plans. The changes will apply to all authorities in the same way. Those areas who deliver the most housing growth will continue to benefit most from the Bonus under the new scheme and bonus payments will remain un-ringfenced so authorities can chose how to allocate the funding to meet local priorities The Government has given local authorities access to up to £7.6 billion in dedicated social care funding over the Spending Review period 2016/20. Taken together with the funding announced at the Spending Review 2015, these new changes mean that local government will have access to the funding it needs to increase social care spending every year in this Parliament.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-02-01T15:00:01.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678531/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678531/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678531/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make it his policy to maintain payments of the New Homes Bonus at the current rate for those local authorities which use the funds received from that bonus to cover the cost of adult social care.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","61618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678532","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-31","<p>Compensation is a matter for negotiation between the acquiring authority and the claimant according to the Compensation Code determined, if necessary, by the Upper Tribunal (Lands Chamber). The Department does not, therefore, have any role in the calculation of compensation in any particular case.</p><p>The Department has published guidance on the compulsory purchase process which can be found at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/472726/151027_Updated_guidance_for_publication_FINAL2.pdf" target="_blank">Guidance</a> in particular see Stage 6 on Compensation.</p><p>There are some additional measures in relation to compensation where the Compulsory Purchase Order includes agricultural land and these can be found in Booklet 3 at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/11489/147645.pdf" target="_blank">Booklet 3</a>.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-31T13:50:15.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678532/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678532/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678532/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Compulsory Purchase: Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what metrics his Department uses to calculate compensation for owners of agricultural land under compulsory purchase.","true","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","61671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678533","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-02","<p>By the end of the Parliament, local government will retain 100 per cent of taxes raised locally, giving councils control of around an additional £12.5 billion of business rates to spend on local services. Councils have long campaigned for this move towards local self-sufficiency. In order that these reforms are revenue neutral, local authorities will have £12.5 billion of additional responsibilities delegated to them. We consulted last Summer on these reforms, including on which additional functions should be delegated, and had over 450 responses. My officials are currently considering all responses and we will publish a summary of the responses and our proposals for the broad way forward in due course.</p><p>If public health responsibilities were to be resourced through retained business rates, then this would change the funding mechanism by which the resource is supplied to local authorities, but would not change the legal requirements on local authorities to improve public health.</p><p>The legislative framework for public health would remain, including regulations mandating particular services. If public health responsibilities were to be resourced through retained business rates then the Government would also consider whether any adjustments to this framework are necessary, and if required the Government would consult on any proposed changes.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","61687 ; 61691 ; 61774","2017-02-02T14:40:08.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678533/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678533/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678533/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Public Health: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 1 December 2016 to Question HL3395, if the Government will hold a public consultation on the effect on future arrangements for public health funding of Government proposals on business rate retention by local authorities.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","61637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678534","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-30","<p>Any property without basic amenities such as drinking water is a potential risk to the health and safety of the occupants. Local authorities have strong powers under the Housing Act 2004 to tackle such situations, including prohibiting the property from being used.</p><p>The Renting a Safe Home Guide is aimed at helping tenants identify hazards of health risks, and provides advice on what to do if the property is unsafe.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-30T16:58:27.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678534/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678534/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678534/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Rented Housing: Water Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department provides on rental of a property without provision of drinking water; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","61747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678535","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-31","<p>Where a household is found to be intentionally homeless, but is in priority need, the local housing authority must also ensure that accommodation is available for long enough to give the applicant a reasonable opportunity to find a home. An applicant can ask the authority to review a decision that they are intentionally homeless and, if still dissatisfied, can appeal to the county court on a point of law. Over the next four years the Government will invest £149 million in central programmes to prevent and reduce homelessness in England. We have also protected and maintained homelessness prevention funding for councils, reaching £315 million by 2019/20, to ensure they can provide advice to all those who approach them for help. In addition, £870 million in Discretionary Housing Payment funding is being provided to councils across the Parliament.</p><p>Homelessness data, including households who are intentionally homeless, is published at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-homelessness" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-homelessness</a></p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-31T13:53:07.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678535/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678535/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678535/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the costs to local authorities of supporting people made intentionally homeless.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","61688"
