"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678537","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-30","<p>At Autumn Statement the Chancellor announced regional Growth Deal awards worth £1.8 billion across England. Individual awards for Northern Powerhouse Local Enterprise Partnerships were announced and published on 23 January. We plan to announce all remaining Local Enterprise Partnership Growth Deal awards over the coming weeks.</p><p> </p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2017-01-30T16:45:35.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678537/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678537/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Local Enterprise Partnerships: Local Growth Deals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to publish information on the Growth Deal allocation for each local enterprise partnership made under the Autumn Statement 2016.","false","Biography information for Anne Marie Morris","Newton Abbot","Anne Marie Morris","61656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678538","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Government published &quot;Business rates retention scheme: the economic benefits of local business rates retention&quot; in May 2012.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-02T13:53:44.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678538/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678538/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678538/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678538/answer/previousversion/32998","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Business Rates Retention Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the economic effect of the introduction of the Business Rate Retention Scheme in April 2013; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","61659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678539","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-06","<p>A note explaining the methodology and the key assumptions that sit behind the estimate of the new burdens costs of the Homelessness Reduction Bill was sent to local authorities and members of the Bill Committee on 17 January. The same methodology underpins the revised new burdens estimate of £61 million I set out at the Report stage of the Homelessness Reduction Bill on 27 January. A copy of the note will be placed in the Library of the House. The Department will continue to work with the Local Government Association and local authorities on the development of the distribution model for the funding to determine the amount to be received by each area. The full new burdens assessment will be published once this is complete and the Bill is in its final form.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-06T17:07:42.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678539/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678539/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678539/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678539/answer/previousversion/32999","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Written Statement of 17 January 2017, Homelessness Reduction Bill, HCWS 418, if he will place in the Library the evidential basis used to determine the level of funding to local government to meet the new burden costs associated with the Homelessness Reduction Bill.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","61704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678540","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-02","<p>By the end of the Parliament, local government will retain 100 per cent of taxes raised locally, giving councils control of around an additional £12.5 billion of business rates to spend on local services. Councils have long campaigned for this move towards local self-sufficiency. In order that these reforms are revenue neutral, local authorities will have £12.5 billion of additional responsibilities delegated to them. We consulted last Summer on these reforms, including on which additional functions should be delegated, and had over 450 responses. My officials are currently considering all responses and we will publish a summary of the responses and our proposals for the broad way forward in due course.</p><p>If public health responsibilities were to be resourced through retained business rates, then this would change the funding mechanism by which the resource is supplied to local authorities, but would not change the legal requirements on local authorities to improve public health.</p><p>The legislative framework for public health would remain, including regulations mandating particular services. If public health responsibilities were to be resourced through retained business rates then the Government would also consider whether any adjustments to this framework are necessary, and if required the Government would consult on any proposed changes.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","61637 ; 61687 ; 61774","2017-02-02T14:40:08.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678540/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678540/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678540/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-25","Non-domestic Rates: Public Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, wha